{"title_page": "Hypatia (journal)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Journal\n| cover = [[File:Cover of Hypatia.jpeg|160px]]\n| discipline = [[Feminist philosophy]]\n| abbreviation = Hypatia\n| editors = [[Bonnie Mann|Bonnie J. Mann]], Erin McKenna, Camisha Russell, and Roc\u00edo Zambrana\n| publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] (from 2020)\n| country = \n| history = 1983\u2013present\n| frequency = Quarterly\n| impact = 0.712<ref name=WileyHapatia>[https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/15272001 \"''Hypatia''\"]. Wiley Online Library (until 2019).</ref>\n| impact-year = 2017\n| website = https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/hypatia \n| link1 = http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001/currentissue\n| link1-name = Online access (until 2019)\n| link2 = http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001/issues\n| link2-name = Online archive (until 2019)\n| link3 = http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/\n| link3-name = Website\n| ISSN = 0887-5367\n| eISSN = 1527-2001\n| OCLC = 243426299\n| LCCN = 87655721\n| JSTOR = 08875367\n}}\n'''''Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy''''' is a [[peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] based in the [[University of Oregon]], [[Eugene]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Halnon |first1=Emily |title=Feminist philosophy journal Hypatia finds a new home at UO |url=https://around.uoregon.edu/content/feminist-philosophy-journal-hypatia-finds-new-home-uo |publisher=University of Oregon |date=24 April 2019}}</ref> Focusing on [[feminist philosophy]], ''Hypatia'' was published quarterly until 2019 by [[Wiley-Blackwell]] and from 2020 will be published by [[Cambridge University Press]]. As of March 2020, the journal is led by co-editors [[Bonnie Mann|Bonnie J. Mann]], Erin McKenna, Camisha Russell, and Roc\u00edo Zambrana.<ref name=HypatiaCUPMarch2020>{{cite web |title=Hypatia |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/hypatia |publisher=Cambridge University Press |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200311032728/https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/hypatia |archivedate=11 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=governanceMarch2020>{{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=hypatiaphilosophy.org |publisher=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200311003016/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=11 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Book reviews are published by ''Hypatia Reviews Online (HRO)''.<ref>[http://hypatiareviews.org/ ''Hypatia Reviews Online''], Department of Philosophy, University of Oregon.</ref> The journal is owned by a non-profit corporation, Hypatia Inc.<ref name=ProPublica>{{cite web|title=Hypatia Inc|url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/262868769|publisher=ProPublica|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200312010041/https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/262868769|archivedate=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe idea for the journal arose out of meetings in the 1970s of the [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] (SWIP).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Trebilcot |first1=Joyce |editor1-last=al-Hibri |editor1-first=Azizah Y. |editor2-last=Simons |editor2-first=Margaret A. |editor1-link=Azizah Y. al-Hibri |title=Hypatia Reborn: Essays in Feminist Philosophy |date=1990 |publisher=Indiana University Press |location=Bloomington and Indianapolis |isbn=0-253-32744-X |chapter=Foreword |pages=ix\u2013x |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy | url = http://pembroke-archives.squarespace.com/hypatia-a-journal-of-feminist-philosophy-1/ | publisher = [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] | access-date = 29 March 2018}}</ref> Philosopher and legal scholar [[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]] became the founding editor in 1982, when it was published as a \"piggy back\" issue of the ''[[Women's Studies International Forum]]''.<ref name=\"Hibri22Oct2009\">{{cite news|last1=Al-Hibri|first1=Azizah Y|url=https://vimeo.com/12221774|title=A Journal of Her Own: Hypatia Founders and Editors|date=22 October 2009|publisher=25th Anniversary Conference: Feminist Legacies/Feminist Futures, University of Washington|at=Courtesy of Vimeo, 00:05:50\u201300:08:15|ref=harv|author-link=Azizah Y. al-Hibri}}</ref> Named after [[Hypatia of Alexandria]], a philosopher who was murdered by a mob in 415&nbsp;CE, it became an independent journal in 1986.<ref name=Gruen2010>{{cite journal |last1=Gruen |first1=Lori |author-link1=Lori Gruen|last2=Wylie|first2=Alison |author-link2=Alison Wylie|title=Feminist Legacies/Feminist Futures: 25th Anniversary Special Issue\u2014Editors' Introduction |journal=Hypatia |date=Fall 2010 |volume=25 |issue=4 |pages=725\u2013732|jstor=40928652|doi=10.1111/j.1527-2001.2010.01141.x }}</ref>\n\n''Hypatia'' became [[#2017 dispute|involved in a damaging dispute]] in 2017 when its associate editors published an unauthorized apology for the journal's publication of an article on [[Transracial (identity)|transracialism]], after the author and article were criticized on [[social media]].<ref name=Singal2May2017/> The episode pointed to a significant breakdown of communications within ''Hypatia''{{'}}s editorial team.<ref name=McKenzie6May2017/><ref name=Brubaker18May2017/><ref name=Schuessler19May2017/> The journal responded by setting up a task force to restructure its governance.<ref name=Weinberg13Nov2017/> It was the [[#2018 hoax|subject of further controversy]] in 2018 when it accepted a satirical hoax article for publication, one of several written as part of the [[Grievance Studies affair|grievance-studies affair]]. The hoaxes were exposed by the ''Wall Street Journal'' before ''Hypatia'' was able to publish the article.<ref name=Schuessler4Oct2018>{{cite news|last=Scheussler |first=Jennifer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/04/arts/academic-journals-hoax.html |title=Hoaxers Slip Breastaurants and Dog-Park Sex Into Journals|work=The New York Times|date=4 October 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181012015807/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/04/arts/academic-journals-hoax.html|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Feminist philosophy}}\n''Hypatia'' has its roots in regional meetings of the [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] (SWIP), established in 1972. One of SWIP's earliest ideas was that it would set up a philosophy journal. The thought of \"[[A Room of One's Own|a journal of our own\"]] was very powerful, according to Kathryn Morgan ([[University of Toronto|Toronto]]), speaking in 2009 on the history of ''Hypatia''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Hypatia (journal)|date=2020-04-14|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Hypatia_(journal)&oldid=950818294|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> At the time, according to [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] ([[City University of New York|CUNY]]), president of the Hypatia Inc. board of directors since February 2018,<ref>{{Citation|title=Hypatia (journal)|date=2020-04-14|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Hypatia_(journal)&oldid=950818294|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> philosophers who wanted to write about gender-related issues were being silenced in a discipline \"riven by unabashed bias and vested interest, inflicting its own form of unapologetic mob violence\".\n\n[[File:Azizah Y. al-Hibri, 2012.jpeg|thumb|right|upright=0.8|[[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]], 2012]]\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\nSWIP decided in 1977 to set up an [[editorial board]] to plan the journal; the first board was put together by [[Ann Garry]] ([[California State University, Los Angeles|Cal State LA]]) and Jacqueline Thomason ([[University of Massachusetts Amherst|UMass Amherst]]). Women's Studies International Forum At a meeting in Denver in the spring of 1979, the board agreed that [[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]] ([[University of Richmond|UR]]) should be the founding editor. Al-Hibri began work on the journal in 1982, after she had completed her PhD in philosophy and just as she was starting her first year of [[law school]]. The philosophy and women's studies departments at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] offered support in the form of an office and research assistance.[[Women's Studies International Forum|''Women's Studies International Forum'']] agreed to publish the new journal as an annual \"piggy back\" issue of its own, which it did for three years, and distributed 10,000 brochures to its mailing list advertising it.\n\nThe group led by Al-Hibri decided that submissions would be fully reviewed and that substantive comments would be offered, Alcoff wrote, rather than the usual brief rejection, to help authors improve their work and to contribute to the field's development. Donna Serniak ([[University of Pennsylvania|Penn]]) was responsible for the first issue. It was first published independently of ''Women's Studies International Forum'' in 1986.\n\nThe journal is named after [[Hypatia of Alexandria]], a mathematician and philosopher who was murdered by a mob in 415 CE. Al-Hibri said that the SWIP editorial board chose the name to reflect that women have \"deep roots in philosophy\". According to [[Linda L\u00f3pez McAlister]] ([[University of South Florida|USF]]), the idea for the name came from Sue Larson ([[Barnard College|Barnard]]) during a meeting of Eastern SWIP in 1973. [[Sandra Harding]] ([[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]), who was at the meeting, objected, thinking it awful to name a feminist-philosophy journal after a woman who had been \"stoned to death for telling the truth\". The first suggestion was ''Hypatia: A Journal of Philosophy and Feminism'', rather than ''A Journal of Feminist Philosophy'', because at the time it was unclear what feminist philosophy might be.\n\nThroughout Hypatia\u2019s thirty-three-year history, the journal has been influential in legitimizing feminist philosophy within the field. It has served as one of the most pivotal sources of scholarship in feminist philosophy, both because it showcases a wide range of feminist viewpoints and because it has self-consciously addressed varied views and issues in the discipline. In a editorial statement titled \u201cThe Promise of Feminist Philosophy,\u201d the editors note that:<blockquote>Hypatia\u2019s specific history in this regard is complex. The journal\u2019s editors have often addressed questions of disciplinary pluralism, demographic exclusion and marginalization, and the journal\u2019s own role in setting the agenda for feminist agitation or compliance within the academy...The special issue structure has sometimes allowed ''Hypatia'' to create space for scholars who are subjected to the most persistent forms of marginalization in the discipline, and for intersectional feminist work, even as ''Hypatia'' as a whole has been justly criticized for the underrepresentation of such work.<ref>[https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/hypa.12490]</ref>...More recently, the development of ''Hypatia'' clusters (a set of two or more articles on a single theme in an open issue) offers another avenue that might be employed to highlight work that is marginalized in the larger discipline.</blockquote>\n\n==Governance==\n''Hypatia'' is owned by a non-profit corporation, Hypatia Inc.,<ref name=ProPublica/> registered in April 2008 in the State of Washington. The purpose of the non-profit is \"to foster feminist scholarship in philosophy and related fields, including through the publication of the academic journal ''Hypatia''\".{{efn|\"A non-profit corporation, Hypatia Inc. (WA), was registered in the state of Washington in April 2008. Its purpose, as stated in the articles of incorporation, is 'to foster feminist scholarship in philosophy and related fields, including through the publication of the academic journal Hypatia.'<ref name=governance>{{cite web|title=''Hypatia'' governance, adopted 26 June 2009 by the Hypatia editors and associate editors|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/pdfs/hypatia_governance.pdf|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043324/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/pdfs/hypatia_governance.pdf|archivedate=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} As of October 2019, the board of directors consisted of [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]], Talia Mae Bettcher, [[Ann Garry]], [[Helen Longino]], [[Jacqueline Scott]], and [[Nancy Tuana]]. In addition, the journal listed an international advisory board of 15 and an 11-strong board of associate editors. Instead of an editor-in-chief, four co-editors were named, [[Bonnie Mann|Bonnie J. Mann]], Erin McKenna, Camisha Russell, and Roc\u00edo Zambrana, and a managing editor, Sarah LaChance Adams. The managing editor of ''Hypatia Reviews Online'' was named as Bj\u00f8rn Kristensen.<ref name=governanceOct2019>{{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=hypatiaphilosophy.org |publisher=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018192940/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=18 October 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Previous editors-in-chief were:<ref name=HonorRoll>{{cite web|title=Hypatia Honor Roll|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/honor_roll_2013.html|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808112927/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/honor_roll_2013.html|archivedate=8 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=26em|\n* [[Azizah al-Hibri]] (1982\u20131984)\n* Margaret Simons (1984\u20131990)\n* [[Linda L\u00f3pez McAlister]] (1990\u20131998), with Cheryl Hall and Joanne Waugh (1995\u20131998)\n* [[Laurie Shrage|Laurie J. Shrage]] and [[Nancy Tuana]] (1998\u20132003)\n* [[Hilde Lindemann]] (2003\u20132008)\n* [[Lori Gruen]] (2008\u20132010) and [[Alison Wylie]] (2008\u20132013)\n* [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] and [[Ann Cudd]] (2010\u20132013)\n* [[Sally Scholz]] (2013\u20132017)\n* [[Ann Garry]] (interim editor, 2018\u20132019)\n}}\n\n=== <u>2018 Revised Governance Structure</u> ===\n\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0 Following the transition to the current editorial team in 2018, the governing bodies of Hypatia collaborated to produce a new governance document in order to facilitate open communication and procedural consistency in cases of conflict.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/hypatia-governance-structure/|title=hypatia governance structure|last=|first=|date=|website=Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The journal also now has two standing committees, the Reparative Response Committee and the Outreach and Ethics Committee, which serves as intermediary bodies in cases where conflict resolution or intra-organizational mediation is necessary. Each committee consists of members from the Non-Profit board, the Editorial Team, and the Associate Editors. The Reparative Response Committee is specifically tasked with meeting annually to monitor the internal operations of the journal and to facilitate communication if disputes arise. The Outreach and Ethics Committee is tasked with outreach, public engagement, and ethics. It will be responsible for addressing such things as hoax submissions, and complaints from authors. It will also engage in an ongoing reflection on Hypatia\u2019s ethical commitments, ensuring that all those involved with Hypatia are aware of, and adhere to, the COPE guidelines. This committee is also responsible for producing an annual report identifying strengths, successes, challenges, and suggestions for improvement in the journals operation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n\nIn February 2020, Hypatia\u2019s governance boards elected a new Board of Associate Editors<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/uncategorized/793/|title=Announcing New Associate Editors|last=|first=|date=February 21, 2020|website=Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>, including:\n\n* Mar\u00eda del Rosario Acosta L\u00f3pez\n* Saray Ayala-Lopez\n* Talia Bettcher\n* [[Ann Cudd]] \n* Vrinda Dalmiya\n* Ver\u00f3nica Gago\n* Dilek Huseyinzadegan\n* Qrescent Mali Mason\n* Krushil Watene\n* Yolonda Wilson\n* Robin Zheng\n\n==2017 dispute{{anchor|2017 dispute}}==\n=== Transracialism article ===\n{{main|Hypatia transracialism controversy}}\n''Hypatia'' became involved in a dispute in April 2017 that led to the [[online shaming]] of one of its authors, Rebecca Tuvel, an [[Academic tenure|untenured]] [[assistant professor]] of philosophy at [[Rhodes College]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]].<ref name=Singal2May2017>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/05/transracialism-article-controversy.html|title=This Is What a Modern-Day Witch Hunt Looks Like|date=2 May 2017|work=New York Magazine|last=Singal |first=Jesse}}</ref><ref name=Weinberg1May2017>{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|title=Philosopher's Article On Transracialism Sparks Controversy (Updated with response from author)|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/05/01/philosophers-article-transracialism-sparks-controversy/|work=Daily Nous|date=1 May 2017}}</ref> The episode pointed to a breakdown of communications within ''Hypatia''{{'}}s editorial team, and to a rift within [[feminism]] and academic [[philosophy]].<ref name=McKenzie6May2017>{{cite news|last1=McKenzie|first1=Lindsay|last2=Harris|first2=Adam|last3=Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z|first3=Fernanda|title=A Journal Article Provoked a Schism in Philosophy. Now the Rifts Are Deepening|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/A-Journal-Article-Provoked-a/240021|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=6 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=Brubaker18May2017>{{cite news|last1=Brubaker|first1=Rogers|author-link=Rogers Brubaker|title=The Uproar Over 'Transracialism'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/18/opinion/the-uproar-over-transracialism.html|work=The New York Times|date=18 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=Schuessler19May2017>{{cite news|last1=Schuessler|first1=Jennifer|title=A Defense of 'Transracial' Identity Roils Philosophy World|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/19/arts/a-defense-of-transracial-identity-roils-philosophy-world.html|work=The New York Times|date=19 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe journal had published Tuvel's article, \"In Defense of Transracialism\", in its spring 2017 edition after the standard double-blind [[Scholarly peer review|peer review]].<ref name=McKenzie6May2017/> Comparing the case of [[Caitlyn Jenner]] to that of [[Rachel Dolezal]], Tuvel argued that \"[s]ince we should accept transgender individuals' decisions to change sexes, we should also accept transracial individuals' decisions to change races.\"<ref name=Tuvel2017>{{cite journal|last1=Tuvel|first1=Rebecca|title=In Defense of Transracialism|journal=Hypatia|date=25 April 2017|volume=32|issue=2|pages=263\u2013278|doi=10.1111/hypa.12327|ref=harv}}</ref> On 28 April the article was criticized on [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]], and Tuvel became the target of personal attacks.<ref name=Oliver7May2017>{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Kelly|author-link=Kelly Oliver|title=If this is feminism|url=http://thephilosophicalsalon.com/if-this-is-feminism-its-been-hijacked-by-the-thought-police/|work=The Philosophical Salon|publisher=Los Angeles Review of Books|date=7 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=Sosis>Sosis, Cliff (5 October 2017). [http://www.whatisitliketobeaphilosopher.com/rebecca-tuvel/ \"Interview with Rebecca Tuvel\"], ''What Is It Like to Be a Philosopher?''.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Tuvel|first=Rebecca|date=Winter 2018|url=https://www.pdcnet.org/C1257B82005A7B6C/file/A70140B8B305A70B8525826B006A6E2D/$FILE/philtoday_2018_0062_0001_0077_0092.pdf|title=Racial Transitions and Controversial Positions: Reply to Taylor, Gordon, Sealey, Hom, and Botts|journal=Philosophy Today|volume=62|issue=1|pages=(73\u201388), 74|doi=10.5840/philtoday2018223200}}</ref> The following day an [[open letter]], listing a member of ''Hypatia''{{'}}s editorial board as its point of contact, urged that the article be retracted.<ref name=Singal2May2017/><ref name=letter>{{cite news |title=Open letter to Hypatia |url=https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1efp9C0MHch_6Kfgtlm0PZ76nirWtcEsqWHcvgidl2mU/viewform?ts=59066d20&edit_requested=true |publisher=Google Docs |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170502164603/https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1efp9C0MHch_6Kfgtlm0PZ76nirWtcEsqWHcvgidl2mU/viewform?ts=59066d20&edit_requested=true |archivedate=2 May 2017 |access-date=3 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> By 2 May the letter had gathered 830 signatures.<ref name=Anderson18May2017>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Elizabeth|last2=Francis|first2=Leslie (Treasurer)|last3=Grasswick|first3=Heidi (Secretary)|last4=Solomon|first4=Miriam (President)|last5=Tessman|first5=Lisa (Chair)|title=Statement From Hypatia Board|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609221247/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|archivedate=9 June 2017|date=18 May 2017}}</ref> The journal distanced itself further from the article on 1 May when an ''Hypatia'' associate editor apologized on the journal's Facebook page for the article's publication, on behalf of \"a majority of the Hypatia's Board of Associated Editors\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Heyes|first1=Cressida|title=To our friends and colleagues in feminist philosophy|url=https://www.facebook.com/hypatia.editorialoffice/posts/1852550825032876|publisher=Hypatia{{'}}s Facebook page|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170501220930/https://www.facebook.com/hypatia.editorialoffice/posts/1852550825032876%23|archivedate=1 May 2017|date=1 May 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=McKenzie1May2017>McKenzie, Lindsay (1 May 2017). [http://www.chronicle.com/blogs/ticker/journal-apologizes-for-article-likening-transracialism-to-transgenderism/118084 \"Journal Apologizes for Article Likening Transracialism to Being Transgender\"]. ''Chronicle of Higher Education''.</ref>{{efn|At the time of the dispute in April\u2013May 2017, the 10 associate editors were [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] ([[CUNY]]),<ref name=Alcoff4May2017/> Ann Cahill ([[Elon University|Elon]]); Kim Hall ([[Appalachian State University|Appalachian]]); [[Cressida Heyes]] ([[University of Alberta|Alberta]]); Karen Jones ([[University of Melbourne|Melbourne]]); Kyoo Lee ([[John Jay College of Criminal Justice|John Jay]]); Mariana Ortega ([[John Carroll University|John Carroll]]); [[\u00c1sta Kristjana Sveinsd\u00f3ttir]] ([[San Francisco State University|SFSU]]); [[Alison Wylie]] ([[University of Washington|Washington]]); and [[George Yancy]] ([[Emory University|Emory]]).<ref name=boardMay2017>{{cite web|title=Hypatia Editorial Board|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/editors.html|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606005257/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/editors.html|archivedate=6 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} The editor-in-chief, Sally Scholz, stood by the article, and the board of directors, led by [[Miriam Solomon]], confirmed that it would not be retracted.<ref name=McKenzie6May2017/>\n\n===Task force===\nIn July 2017 Scholz resigned as editor-in-chief, along with Shelley Wilcox, editor of ''Hypatia Reviews Online''. The board of directors announced that a task force would restructure the journal's governance, and that anyone in an editorial or non-board position with ''Hypatia'' would be \"required to sign a statement of adherence to guidelines issued by COPE, the [[Committee on Publication Ethics]]\".<ref name=resignation>{{cite web |title=Board of Directors' Statement (July 20, 2017) |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/statements/board-directors-statement-july-20-2017/ |website=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724105806/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/statements/board-directors-statement-july-20-2017/ |date=20 July 2017|archivedate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=interim>{{cite web|title=Continuation of Interim Editorial Team|url=http://www.hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|publisher=Hypatia News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043838/http://www.hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|date=20 July 2017|archivedate=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Weinberg3Aug2017>{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|title=Further Developments at Hypatia|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/08/03/further-developments-at-hypatia/|work=Daily Nous|date=3 August 2017}}</ref> According to a statement from the associate editors, whose role was to choose the next editor, the board of directors asked them, on 17 July, to resign or the journal's governance documents would be suspended, which would remove the associate editors' influence. Eight of the associate editors resigned. In their resignation statement, they wrote that the current controversy was \"grounded in long-standing differences and tensions within the field.\" They argued that feminist philosophy had an ethical commitment to transform philosophy into \"a discipline that honors the perspectives and welcomes the scholarly contributions of historically marginalized groups, including people of color, trans* people, disabled people, and queer people.\"<ref name=Weinberg24July2017>{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|title=Hypatia's Associate Editors Resign|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/07/24/hypatias-associate-editors-resign/|work=Daily Nous|date=24 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Flaherty|first1=Colleen|title=(Another) Shake-Up at 'Hypatia'|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/07/24/divisions-within-hypatias-editorial-board-lead-resignations-top-editors|work=Inside Higher Ed|date=24 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z21July2017>{{cite news|last1=Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z|first1=Fernanda|title=Months After 'Transracialism' Flap, Controversy Still Rages at Feminist Philosophy Journal|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Months-After/240722|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe board appointed interim editors, and in November 2017 [[Sally Haslanger]], Serene Khader, and Yannik Thiem were named as the governance task-force co-chairs.<ref name=Weinberg13Nov2017>{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|title=Hypatia Board Announces Task Force|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/11/13/hypatia-board-announces-task-force/|work=Daily Nous|date=13 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=taskforce>{{cite news|title=Hypatia Board of Directors Announces Task Force Co-Chairs|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/task-force/hypatia-board-directors-announces-task-force-co-chairs/|work=Hypatia|date=1 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724115800/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/task-force/hypatia-board-directors-announces-task-force-co-chairs/|archivedate=24 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=EditorialBoardMarch2018>{{cite web|title=Editorial board|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/editorialboard/|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301224919/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/editorialboard/|archivedate=1 March 2018|date=1 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The five-person board of directors, including Solomon, was replaced in February 2018.<ref name=search23Feb2018/> Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff and Kim Hall, two of the associate editors who resigned in July,<ref name=Weinberg24July2017/> became president of the board of directors and chair of the search committee for the new editorial team, respectively.<ref name=search23Feb2018>{{cite web|title=Announcement from Hypatia's Board of Directors and Task Force Co-Chairs|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/announcements/announcement-hypatias-board-directors-task-force-co-chairs/|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164503/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/announcements/announcement-hypatias-board-directors-task-force-co-chairs/|archivedate=1 March 2018|date=23 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=edandgovJuly2018>{{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724092156/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=24 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==2018 hoax==\n{{main|Grievance studies affair}}\n''Hypatia'' was the subject of further controversy in 2018 when it accepted a satirical hoax article for publication, one of several written as part of the \"grievance-studies affair\", organized by, among others, the philosopher [[Peter Boghossian]] to provoke discussion about scholarly standards. Twenty bogus papers were submitted to several journals in the humanities and social sciences.<ref name=Schuessler4Oct2018/><ref name=FactSheet>{{cite web |title=Project Fact Sheet |url=https://leiterreports.typepad.com/files/project-summary-and-fact-sheet.pdf |website=Leiter Reports |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031091213/https://leiterreports.typepad.com/files/project-summary-and-fact-sheet.pdf |archivedate=31 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Two were submitted to ''Hypatia''.<ref name=Weinberg3Oct2018/>\n\nThe first paper, \"The Progressive Stack: An Intersectional Feminist Approach to Pedagogy\", was not accepted; the authors were three times advised to revise and resubmit. The paper suggested that \"educators should discriminate by identity and calculate their students\u2019 status in terms of privilege, favor the least privileged with more time, attention and positive feedback and penalize the most privileged by declining to hear their contributions, deriding their input, intentionally speaking over them, and making them sit on the floor in chains&nbsp;...\"<ref name=Weinberg3Oct2018/> One ''Hypatia'' reviewer reportedly asked how privileged students could be made to \"feel genuinely uncomfortable in ways that are humbling and productive\", but not \"so uncomfortable (shame) that they resist with renewed vigor\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leiter |first1=Brian |author-link=Brian Leiter |title=Sokal Hoax, redux |url=https://leiterreports.typepad.com/blog/2018/10/sokal-hoax-redux.html |website=Leiter Reports |date=3 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=FactSheet/>\n\nThe second paper, \"When the Joke Is on You: A Feminist Perspective on How Positionality Influences Satire\", was accepted.<ref name=Weinberg3Oct2018>{{cite web |last1=Weinberg |first1=Justin |title=Hypatia and other Journals Successfully Tricked Into Accepting 'Fake' Papers (Updated) |url=http://dailynous.com/2018/10/03/hypatia-journals-successfully-tricked-accepting-fake-papers/ |work=Daily Nous |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005085145/http://dailynous.com/2018/10/03/hypatia-journals-successfully-tricked-accepting-fake-papers/ |archivedate=5 October 2018 |date=3 October 2018}}</ref> The paper argued that \"satirical or ironic critique of social justice scholarship are unethical, characterized by ignorance, and rooted in a desire to preserve privilege\", although the same kind of critique would be acceptable in fields such as economics.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mounk|first=Yascha|author-link=Yascha Mounk |title= The Circling of the Academic Wagons |url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/What-the-Grievance/244753 |work=The Chronicle of Higher Education |date=9 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20181101222953/https://www.chronicle.com/article/What-the-Grievance/244753 |archivedate=1 November 2018 |url-status=live}}.</ref><ref name=Weinberg3Oct2018/><ref name=FactSheet/> The ''Wall Street Journal'' exposed the hoax before ''Hypatia'' had published the article.<ref name=Schuessler4Oct2018/>\n\n==Abstracting and indexing==\n''Hypatia'' is [[abstracting and indexing|abstracted and indexed]] in the following [[bibliographic databases]]:<ref>{{cite web<!--Citation bot deny--> |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001/homepage/ProductInformation.html |title=Overview |work=Hypathia |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell}}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=26em|\n*[[Arts and Humanities Citation Index]]<ref name=ISI>{{cite web |url=http://ip-science.thomsonreuters.com/mjl/ |title=Master Journal List |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |work=Intellectual Property & Science |accessdate=2017-07-25}}</ref>\n*[[Current Contents]]/Arts & Humanities<ref name=ISI/>\n*Current Contents/Social & Behavioral Sciences<ref name=ISI/>\n*[[EBSCO Information Services|EBSCO databases]]\n*[[International Bibliography of Periodical Literature]]\n*[[International Political Science Abstracts]]\n*[[MLA International Bibliography]]\n*[[Philosopher's Index]]\n*[[PhilPapers]]\n*[[ProQuest|ProQuest databases]]\n*[[Scopus]] <ref name=Scopus>{{cite web |url=https://www.scopus.com/sourceid/23699 |title=Source details: Hypatia |publisher=[[Elsevier]] |work=Scopus preview |accessdate=2017-07-25}}</ref>\n*[[Social Science Citation Index]]<ref name=ISI/>\n*[[Sociological Abstracts]]\n}}\nAccording to the ''[[Journal Citation Reports]]'', the journal has a 2017 [[impact factor]] of 0.712.<ref name=WoS>{{cite book |year=2018 |chapter=Hypatia |title=2017 Journal Citation Reports |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |edition=Social Sciences |series=[[Web of Science]]|title-link=Journal Citation Reports }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of women's studies journals]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|26em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Official|http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001}}\n* {{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724092156/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}\n* [[Azizah Y. al-Hibri|Al-Hibri, Azizah Y.]] and Simons, Margaret A. (1990). ''Hypatia Reborn: Essays in Feminist Philosophy''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press.\n* Berm\u00fadez, Jos\u00e9 Luis (5 May 2017). [https://www.insidehighered.com/views/2017/05/05/real-damage-done-flare-over-philosophers-journal-article-essay \"Defining \u2018Harm\u2019 in the Tuvel Affair\"], ''Inside Higher Ed''.\n* Glancy, Josh (7 May 2017). [https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/world/philosopher-lashed-for-backing-transracial-pioneer-ndc0btdjt \"Philosopher lashed for backing \u2018transracial\u2019 pioneer\"], ''The Times''.\n* [[Laurie Shrage|Shrage, Laurie]] (22 May 2017). [http://dailynous.com/2017/05/22/feminist-philosophy-controversies-guest-post-laurie-shrage/ \"Feminist Philosophy and Its Controversies\"], ''Daily Nous''.\n* {{cite news|last1=Walters|first1=Suzanna Danuta|author-link=Suzanna Danuta Walters|title=Academe's Poisonous Call-Out Culture|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Academe-s-Poisonous-Call-Out/240016|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=5 May 2017}}\n*[https://www.ualberta.ca/post-doctoral-fellows-association/news-events/events/arts/1cgp8su5thbt8hajc16e5h7po9 \"Social Justice, Feminist Affects & Philosophical Futures: A Symposium Responding to the Hypatia Controversy\"], University of Alberta, 7 March 2018.\n*[https://www.pdcnet.org/collection-anonymous/browse?fp=philtoday&fq=philtoday%2fVolume%2f8938%7c62%2f8999%7cIssue%3a+1%2f \"Special symposium: Rebecca Tuvel and her interlocutors\"], ''Philosophy Today''. 62(1), Winter 2018.\n\n{{philosophy topics}}\n{{feminism}}\n{{Philosophy journals|state=collapsed}}\n{{portal bar|Feminism|Philosophy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy}}\n[[Category:English-language journals]]\n[[Category:Feminism and society]]\n[[Category:Feminist journals]]\n[[Category:Feminist philosophy]]\n[[Category:Gender studies journals]]\n[[Category:Wiley-Blackwell academic journals]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Philosophy journals]]\n[[Category:Quarterly journals]]\n[[Category:Women's mass media]]\n[[Category:Women's studies journals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Journal\n| cover = [[File:Cover of Hypatia.jpeg|160px]]\n| discipline = [[Feminist philosophy]]\n| abbreviation = Hypatia\n| editors = [[Bonnie Mann|Bonnie J. Mann]], Erin McKenna, Camisha Russell, and Roc\u00edo Zambrana\n| publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] (from 2020)\n| country = \n| history = 1983\u2013present\n| frequency = Quarterly\n| impact = 0.712<ref name=WileyHapatia>[https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/15272001 \"''Hypatia''\"]. Wiley Online Library (until 2019).</ref>\n| impact-year = 2017\n| website = https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/hypatia \n| link1 = http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001/currentissue\n| link1-name = Online access (until 2019)\n| link2 = http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001/issues\n| link2-name = Online archive (until 2019)\n| link3 = http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/\n| link3-name = Website\n| ISSN = 0887-5367\n| eISSN = 1527-2001\n| OCLC = 243426299\n| LCCN = 87655721\n| JSTOR = 08875367\n}}\n'''''Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy''''' is a [[peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] based in the [[University of Oregon]], [[Eugene]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Halnon |first1=Emily |title=Feminist philosophy journal Hypatia finds a new home at UO |url=https://around.uoregon.edu/content/feminist-philosophy-journal-hypatia-finds-new-home-uo |publisher=University of Oregon |date=24 April 2019}}</ref> Focusing on [[feminist philosophy]], ''Hypatia'' was published quarterly until 2019 by [[Wiley-Blackwell]] and from 2020 will be published by [[Cambridge University Press]]. As of March 2020, the journal is led by co-editors [[Bonnie Mann|Bonnie J. Mann]], Erin McKenna, Camisha Russell, and Roc\u00edo Zambrana.<ref name=HypatiaCUPMarch2020>{{cite web |title=Hypatia |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/hypatia |publisher=Cambridge University Press |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200311032728/https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/hypatia |archivedate=11 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=governanceMarch2020>{{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=hypatiaphilosophy.org |publisher=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200311003016/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=11 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Book reviews are published by ''Hypatia Reviews Online (HRO)''.<ref>[http://hypatiareviews.org/ ''Hypatia Reviews Online''], Department of Philosophy, University of Oregon.</ref> The journal is owned by a non-profit corporation, Hypatia Inc.<ref name=ProPublica>{{cite web|title=Hypatia Inc|url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/262868769|publisher=ProPublica|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200312010041/https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/262868769|archivedate=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe idea for the journal arose out of meetings in the 1970s of the [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] (SWIP).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Trebilcot |first1=Joyce |editor1-last=al-Hibri |editor1-first=Azizah Y. |editor2-last=Simons |editor2-first=Margaret A. |editor1-link=Azizah Y. al-Hibri |title=Hypatia Reborn: Essays in Feminist Philosophy |date=1990 |publisher=Indiana University Press |location=Bloomington and Indianapolis |isbn=0-253-32744-X |chapter=Foreword |pages=ix\u2013x |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy | url = http://pembroke-archives.squarespace.com/hypatia-a-journal-of-feminist-philosophy-1/ | publisher = [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] | access-date = 29 March 2018}}</ref> Philosopher and legal scholar [[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]] became the founding editor in 1982, when it was published as a \"piggy back\" issue of the ''[[Women's Studies International Forum]]''.<ref name=\"Hibri22Oct2009\">{{cite news|last1=Al-Hibri|first1=Azizah Y|url=https://vimeo.com/12221774|title=A Journal of Her Own: Hypatia Founders and Editors|date=22 October 2009|publisher=25th Anniversary Conference: Feminist Legacies/Feminist Futures, University of Washington|at=Courtesy of Vimeo, 00:05:50\u201300:08:15|ref=harv|author-link=Azizah Y. al-Hibri}}</ref> Named after [[Hypatia of Alexandria]], a philosopher who was murdered by a mob in 415&nbsp;CE, it became an independent journal in 1986.<ref name=Gruen2010>{{cite journal |last1=Gruen |first1=Lori |author-link1=Lori Gruen|last2=Wylie|first2=Alison |author-link2=Alison Wylie|title=Feminist Legacies/Feminist Futures: 25th Anniversary Special Issue\u2014Editors' Introduction |journal=Hypatia |date=Fall 2010 |volume=25 |issue=4 |pages=725\u2013732|jstor=40928652|doi=10.1111/j.1527-2001.2010.01141.x }}</ref>\n\n''Hypatia'' became [[#2017 dispute|involved in a damaging dispute]] in 2017 when its associate editors published an unauthorized apology for the journal's publication of an article on [[Transracial (identity)|transracialism]], after the author and article were criticized on [[social media]].<ref name=Singal2May2017/> The episode pointed to a significant breakdown of communications within ''Hypatia''{{'}}s editorial team.<ref name=McKenzie6May2017/><ref name=Brubaker18May2017/><ref name=Schuessler19May2017/> The journal responded by setting up a task force to restructure its governance.<ref name=Weinberg13Nov2017/> It was the [[#2018 hoax|subject of further controversy]] in 2018 when it accepted a satirical hoax article for publication, one of several written as part of the [[Grievance Studies affair|grievance-studies affair]]. The hoaxes were exposed by the ''Wall Street Journal'' before ''Hypatia'' was able to publish the article.<ref name=Schuessler4Oct2018>{{cite news|last=Scheussler |first=Jennifer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/04/arts/academic-journals-hoax.html |title=Hoaxers Slip Breastaurants and Dog-Park Sex Into Journals|work=The New York Times|date=4 October 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181012015807/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/04/arts/academic-journals-hoax.html|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Feminist philosophy}}\n''Hypatia'' has its roots in regional meetings of the [[Society for Women in Philosophy]] (SWIP), established in 1972. One of SWIP's earliest ideas was that it would set up a philosophy journal. The thought of \"[[A Room of One's Own|a journal of our own\"]] was very powerful, according to Kathryn Morgan ([[University of Toronto|Toronto]]), speaking in 2009 on the history of ''Hypatia''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Hypatia (journal)|date=2020-04-14|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Hypatia_(journal)&oldid=950818294|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> At the time, according to [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] ([[City University of New York|CUNY]]), president of the Hypatia Inc. board of directors since February 2018,<ref>{{Citation|title=Hypatia (journal)|date=2020-04-14|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Hypatia_(journal)&oldid=950818294|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> philosophers who wanted to write about gender-related issues were being silenced in a discipline \"riven by unabashed bias and vested interest, inflicting its own form of unapologetic mob violence\".\n\n[[File:Azizah Y. al-Hibri, 2012.jpeg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|[[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]], 2012]]\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\nSWIP decided in 1977 to set up an [[editorial board]] to plan the journal; the first board was put together by [[Ann Garry]] ([[California State University, Los Angeles|Cal State LA]]) and Jacqueline Thomason ([[University of Massachusetts Amherst|UMass Amherst]]). Women's Studies International Forum At a meeting in Denver in the spring of 1979, the board agreed that [[Azizah Y. al-Hibri]] ([[University of Richmond|UR]]) should be the founding editor. Al-Hibri began work on the journal in 1982, after she had completed her PhD in philosophy and just as she was starting her first year of [[law school]]. The philosophy and women's studies departments at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] offered support in the form of an office and research assistance.[[Women's Studies International Forum|''Women's Studies International Forum'']] agreed to publish the new journal as an annual \"piggy back\" issue of its own, which it did for three years, and distributed 10,000 brochures to its mailing list advertising it.\n\nThe group led by Al-Hibri decided that submissions would be fully reviewed and that substantive comments would be offered, Alcoff wrote, rather than the usual brief rejection, to help authors improve their work and to contribute to the field's development. Donna Serniak ([[University of Pennsylvania|Penn]]) was responsible for the first issue. It was first published independently of ''Women's Studies International Forum'' in 1986.\n\nThe journal is named after [[Hypatia of Alexandria]], a mathematician and philosopher who was murdered by a mob in 415 CE. Al-Hibri said that the SWIP editorial board chose the name to reflect that women have \"deep roots in philosophy\". According to [[Linda L\u00f3pez McAlister]] ([[University of South Florida|USF]]), the idea for the name came from Sue Larson ([[Barnard College|Barnard]]) during a meeting of Eastern SWIP in 1973. [[Sandra Harding]] ([[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]), who was at the meeting, objected, thinking it awful to name a feminist-philosophy journal after a woman who had been \"stoned to death for telling the truth\". The first suggestion was ''Hypatia: A Journal of Philosophy and Feminism'', rather than ''A Journal of Feminist Philosophy'', because at the time it was unclear what feminist philosophy might be.\n\nThroughout Hypatia\u2019s thirty-three-year history, the journal has been influential in legitimizing feminist philosophy within the field. It has served as one of the most pivotal sources of scholarship in feminist philosophy, both because it showcases a wide range of feminist viewpoints and because it has self-consciously addressed varied views and issues in the discipline. In a editorial statement titled \u201cThe Promise of Feminist Philosophy,\u201d the editors note that:<blockquote>Hypatia\u2019s specific history in this regard is complex. The journal\u2019s editors have often addressed questions of disciplinary pluralism, demographic exclusion and marginalization, and the journal\u2019s own role in setting the agenda for feminist agitation or compliance within the academy...The special issue structure has sometimes allowed ''Hypatia'' to create space for scholars who are subjected to the most persistent forms of marginalization in the discipline, and for intersectional feminist work, even as ''Hypatia'' as a whole has been justly criticized for the underrepresentation of such work.<ref>[https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/hypa.12490]</ref>...More recently, the development of ''Hypatia'' clusters (a set of two or more articles on a single theme in an open issue) offers another avenue that might be employed to highlight work that is marginalized in the larger discipline.</blockquote>\n\n==Governance==\n''Hypatia'' is owned by a non-profit corporation, Hypatia Inc.,<ref name=ProPublica/> registered in April 2008 in the State of Washington. The purpose of the non-profit is \"to foster feminist scholarship in philosophy and related fields, including through the publication of the academic journal ''Hypatia''\".{{efn|\"A non-profit corporation, Hypatia Inc. (WA), was registered in the state of Washington in April 2008. Its purpose, as stated in the articles of incorporation, is 'to foster feminist scholarship in philosophy and related fields, including through the publication of the academic journal Hypatia.'<ref name=governance>{{cite web|title=''Hypatia'' governance, adopted 26 June 2009 by the Hypatia editors and associate editors|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/pdfs/hypatia_governance.pdf|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043324/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/pdfs/hypatia_governance.pdf|archivedate=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} As of October 2019, the board of directors consisted of [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]], Talia Mae Bettcher, [[Ann Garry]], [[Helen Longino]], [[Jacqueline Scott]], and [[Nancy Tuana]]. In addition, the journal listed an international advisory board of 15 and an 11-strong board of associate editors. Instead of an editor-in-chief, four co-editors were named, [[Bonnie Mann|Bonnie J. Mann]], Erin McKenna, Camisha Russell, and Roc\u00edo Zambrana, and a managing editor, Sarah LaChance Adams. The managing editor of ''Hypatia Reviews Online'' was named as Bj\u00f8rn Kristensen.<ref name=governanceOct2019>{{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=hypatiaphilosophy.org |publisher=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018192940/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=18 October 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Previous editors-in-chief were:<ref name=HonorRoll>{{cite web|title=Hypatia Honor Roll|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/honor_roll_2013.html|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808112927/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/honor_roll_2013.html|archivedate=8 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=26em|\n* [[Azizah al-Hibri]] (1982\u20131984)\n* Margaret Simons (1984\u20131990)\n* [[Linda L\u00f3pez McAlister]] (1990\u20131998), with Cheryl Hall and Joanne Waugh (1995\u20131998)\n* [[Laurie Shrage|Laurie J. Shrage]] and [[Nancy Tuana]] (1998\u20132003)\n* [[Hilde Lindemann]] (2003\u20132008)\n* [[Lori Gruen]] (2008\u20132010) and [[Alison Wylie]] (2008\u20132013)\n* [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] and [[Ann Cudd]] (2010\u20132013)\n* [[Sally Scholz]] (2013\u20132017)\n* [[Ann Garry]] (interim editor, 2018\u20132019)\n}}\n\n=== <u>2018 Revised Governance Structure</u> ===\n\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0 Following the transition to the current editorial team in 2018, the governing bodies of Hypatia collaborated to produce a new governance document in order to facilitate open communication and procedural consistency in cases of conflict.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/hypatia-governance-structure/|title=hypatia governance structure|last=|first=|date=|website=Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The journal also now has two standing committees, the Reparative Response Committee and the Outreach and Ethics Committee, which serves as intermediary bodies in cases where conflict resolution or intra-organizational mediation is necessary. Each committee consists of members from the Non-Profit board, the Editorial Team, and the Associate Editors. The Reparative Response Committee is specifically tasked with meeting annually to monitor the internal operations of the journal and to facilitate communication if disputes arise. The Outreach and Ethics Committee is tasked with outreach, public engagement, and ethics. It will be responsible for addressing such things as hoax submissions, and complaints from authors. It will also engage in an ongoing reflection on Hypatia\u2019s ethical commitments, ensuring that all those involved with Hypatia are aware of, and adhere to, the COPE guidelines. This committee is also responsible for producing an annual report identifying strengths, successes, challenges, and suggestions for improvement in the journals operation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n\nIn February 2020, Hypatia\u2019s governance boards elected a new Board of Associate Editors<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/uncategorized/793/|title=Announcing New Associate Editors|last=|first=|date=February 21, 2020|website=Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>, including:\n\n* Mar\u00eda del Rosario Acosta L\u00f3pez\n* Saray Ayala-Lopez\n* Talia Bettcher\n* [[Ann Cudd]] \n* Vrinda Dalmiya\n* Ver\u00f3nica Gago\n* Dilek Huseyinzadegan\n* Qrescent Mali Mason\n* Krushil Watene\n* Yolonda Wilson\n* Robin Zheng\n\n==2017 dispute{{anchor|2017 dispute}}==\n=== Transracialism article ===\n{{main|Hypatia transracialism controversy}}\n''Hypatia'' became involved in a dispute in April 2017 that led to the [[online shaming]] of one of its authors, Rebecca Tuvel, an [[Academic tenure|untenured]] [[assistant professor]] of philosophy at [[Rhodes College]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]].<ref name=Singal2May2017>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/05/transracialism-article-controversy.html|title=This Is What a Modern-Day Witch Hunt Looks Like|date=2 May 2017|work=New York Magazine|last=Singal |first=Jesse}}</ref><ref name=Weinberg1May2017>{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|title=Philosopher's Article On Transracialism Sparks Controversy (Updated with response from author)|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/05/01/philosophers-article-transracialism-sparks-controversy/|work=Daily Nous|date=1 May 2017}}</ref> The episode pointed to a breakdown of communications within ''Hypatia''{{'}}s editorial team, and to a rift within [[feminism]] and academic [[philosophy]].<ref name=McKenzie6May2017>{{cite news|last1=McKenzie|first1=Lindsay|last2=Harris|first2=Adam|last3=Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z|first3=Fernanda|title=A Journal Article Provoked a Schism in Philosophy. Now the Rifts Are Deepening|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/A-Journal-Article-Provoked-a/240021|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=6 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=Brubaker18May2017>{{cite news|last1=Brubaker|first1=Rogers|author-link=Rogers Brubaker|title=The Uproar Over 'Transracialism'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/18/opinion/the-uproar-over-transracialism.html|work=The New York Times|date=18 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=Schuessler19May2017>{{cite news|last1=Schuessler|first1=Jennifer|title=A Defense of 'Transracial' Identity Roils Philosophy World|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/19/arts/a-defense-of-transracial-identity-roils-philosophy-world.html|work=The New York Times|date=19 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe journal had published Tuvel's article, \"In Defense of Transracialism\", in its spring 2017 edition after the standard double-blind [[Scholarly peer review|peer review]].<ref name=McKenzie6May2017/> Comparing the case of [[Caitlyn Jenner]] to that of [[Rachel Dolezal]], Tuvel argued that \"[s]ince we should accept transgender individuals' decisions to change sexes, we should also accept transracial individuals' decisions to change races.\"<ref name=Tuvel2017>{{cite journal|last1=Tuvel|first1=Rebecca|title=In Defense of Transracialism|journal=Hypatia|date=25 April 2017|volume=32|issue=2|pages=263\u2013278|doi=10.1111/hypa.12327|ref=harv}}</ref> On 28 April the article was criticized on [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]], and Tuvel became the target of personal attacks.<ref name=Oliver7May2017>{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Kelly|author-link=Kelly Oliver|title=If this is feminism|url=http://thephilosophicalsalon.com/if-this-is-feminism-its-been-hijacked-by-the-thought-police/|work=The Philosophical Salon|publisher=Los Angeles Review of Books|date=7 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=Sosis>Sosis, Cliff (5 October 2017). [http://www.whatisitliketobeaphilosopher.com/rebecca-tuvel/ \"Interview with Rebecca Tuvel\"], ''What Is It Like to Be a Philosopher?''.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Tuvel|first=Rebecca|date=Winter 2018|url=https://www.pdcnet.org/C1257B82005A7B6C/file/A70140B8B305A70B8525826B006A6E2D/$FILE/philtoday_2018_0062_0001_0077_0092.pdf|title=Racial Transitions and Controversial Positions: Reply to Taylor, Gordon, Sealey, Hom, and Botts|journal=Philosophy Today|volume=62|issue=1|pages=(73\u201388), 74|doi=10.5840/philtoday2018223200}}</ref> The following day an [[open letter]], listing a member of ''Hypatia''{{'}}s editorial board as its point of contact, urged that the article be retracted.<ref name=Singal2May2017/><ref name=letter>{{cite news |title=Open letter to Hypatia |url=https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1efp9C0MHch_6Kfgtlm0PZ76nirWtcEsqWHcvgidl2mU/viewform?ts=59066d20&edit_requested=true |publisher=Google Docs |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170502164603/https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1efp9C0MHch_6Kfgtlm0PZ76nirWtcEsqWHcvgidl2mU/viewform?ts=59066d20&edit_requested=true |archivedate=2 May 2017 |access-date=3 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> By 2 May the letter had gathered 830 signatures.<ref name=Anderson18May2017>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Elizabeth|last2=Francis|first2=Leslie (Treasurer)|last3=Grasswick|first3=Heidi (Secretary)|last4=Solomon|first4=Miriam (President)|last5=Tessman|first5=Lisa (Chair)|title=Statement From Hypatia Board|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609221247/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|archivedate=9 June 2017|date=18 May 2017}}</ref> The journal distanced itself further from the article on 1 May when an ''Hypatia'' associate editor apologized on the journal's Facebook page for the article's publication, on behalf of \"a majority of the Hypatia's Board of Associated Editors\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Heyes|first1=Cressida|title=To our friends and colleagues in feminist philosophy|url=https://www.facebook.com/hypatia.editorialoffice/posts/1852550825032876|publisher=Hypatia{{'}}s Facebook page|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170501220930/https://www.facebook.com/hypatia.editorialoffice/posts/1852550825032876%23|archivedate=1 May 2017|date=1 May 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=McKenzie1May2017>McKenzie, Lindsay (1 May 2017). [http://www.chronicle.com/blogs/ticker/journal-apologizes-for-article-likening-transracialism-to-transgenderism/118084 \"Journal Apologizes for Article Likening Transracialism to Being Transgender\"]. ''Chronicle of Higher Education''.</ref>{{efn|At the time of the dispute in April\u2013May 2017, the 10 associate editors were [[Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff]] ([[CUNY]]),<ref name=Alcoff4May2017/> Ann Cahill ([[Elon University|Elon]]); Kim Hall ([[Appalachian State University|Appalachian]]); [[Cressida Heyes]] ([[University of Alberta|Alberta]]); Karen Jones ([[University of Melbourne|Melbourne]]); Kyoo Lee ([[John Jay College of Criminal Justice|John Jay]]); Mariana Ortega ([[John Carroll University|John Carroll]]); [[\u00c1sta Kristjana Sveinsd\u00f3ttir]] ([[San Francisco State University|SFSU]]); [[Alison Wylie]] ([[University of Washington|Washington]]); and [[George Yancy]] ([[Emory University|Emory]]).<ref name=boardMay2017>{{cite web|title=Hypatia Editorial Board|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/editors.html|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606005257/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/editors.html|archivedate=6 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} The editor-in-chief, Sally Scholz, stood by the article, and the board of directors, led by [[Miriam Solomon]], confirmed that it would not be retracted.<ref name=McKenzie6May2017/>\n\n===Task force===\nIn July 2017 Scholz resigned as editor-in-chief, along with Shelley Wilcox, editor of ''Hypatia Reviews Online''. The board of directors announced that a task force would restructure the journal's governance, and that anyone in an editorial or non-board position with ''Hypatia'' would be \"required to sign a statement of adherence to guidelines issued by COPE, the [[Committee on Publication Ethics]]\".<ref name=resignation>{{cite web |title=Board of Directors' Statement (July 20, 2017) |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/statements/board-directors-statement-july-20-2017/ |website=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724105806/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/statements/board-directors-statement-july-20-2017/ |date=20 July 2017|archivedate=24 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=interim>{{cite web|title=Continuation of Interim Editorial Team|url=http://www.hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|publisher=Hypatia News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043838/http://www.hypatiaphilosophy.org/Editorial/index.html|date=20 July 2017|archivedate=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Weinberg3Aug2017>{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|title=Further Developments at Hypatia|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/08/03/further-developments-at-hypatia/|work=Daily Nous|date=3 August 2017}}</ref> According to a statement from the associate editors, whose role was to choose the next editor, the board of directors asked them, on 17 July, to resign or the journal's governance documents would be suspended, which would remove the associate editors' influence. Eight of the associate editors resigned. In their resignation statement, they wrote that the current controversy was \"grounded in long-standing differences and tensions within the field.\" They argued that feminist philosophy had an ethical commitment to transform philosophy into \"a discipline that honors the perspectives and welcomes the scholarly contributions of historically marginalized groups, including people of color, trans* people, disabled people, and queer people.\"<ref name=Weinberg24July2017>{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|title=Hypatia's Associate Editors Resign|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/07/24/hypatias-associate-editors-resign/|work=Daily Nous|date=24 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Flaherty|first1=Colleen|title=(Another) Shake-Up at 'Hypatia'|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/07/24/divisions-within-hypatias-editorial-board-lead-resignations-top-editors|work=Inside Higher Ed|date=24 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z21July2017>{{cite news|last1=Zamudio-Suar\u00e9z|first1=Fernanda|title=Months After 'Transracialism' Flap, Controversy Still Rages at Feminist Philosophy Journal|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Months-After/240722|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe board appointed interim editors, and in November 2017 [[Sally Haslanger]], Serene Khader, and Yannik Thiem were named as the governance task-force co-chairs.<ref name=Weinberg13Nov2017>{{cite news|last1=Weinberg|first1=Justin|title=Hypatia Board Announces Task Force|url=http://dailynous.com/2017/11/13/hypatia-board-announces-task-force/|work=Daily Nous|date=13 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=taskforce>{{cite news|title=Hypatia Board of Directors Announces Task Force Co-Chairs|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/task-force/hypatia-board-directors-announces-task-force-co-chairs/|work=Hypatia|date=1 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724115800/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/task-force/hypatia-board-directors-announces-task-force-co-chairs/|archivedate=24 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=EditorialBoardMarch2018>{{cite web|title=Editorial board|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/editorialboard/|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301224919/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/editorialboard/|archivedate=1 March 2018|date=1 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The five-person board of directors, including Solomon, was replaced in February 2018.<ref name=search23Feb2018/> Linda Mart\u00edn Alcoff and Kim Hall, two of the associate editors who resigned in July,<ref name=Weinberg24July2017/> became president of the board of directors and chair of the search committee for the new editorial team, respectively.<ref name=search23Feb2018>{{cite web|title=Announcement from Hypatia's Board of Directors and Task Force Co-Chairs|url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/announcements/announcement-hypatias-board-directors-task-force-co-chairs/|publisher=Hypatia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164503/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/announcements/announcement-hypatias-board-directors-task-force-co-chairs/|archivedate=1 March 2018|date=23 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=edandgovJuly2018>{{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724092156/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=24 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==2018 hoax==\n{{main|Grievance studies affair}}\n''Hypatia'' was the subject of further controversy in 2018 when it accepted a satirical hoax article for publication, one of several written as part of the \"grievance-studies affair\", organized by, among others, the philosopher [[Peter Boghossian]] to provoke discussion about scholarly standards. Twenty bogus papers were submitted to several journals in the humanities and social sciences.<ref name=Schuessler4Oct2018/><ref name=FactSheet>{{cite web |title=Project Fact Sheet |url=https://leiterreports.typepad.com/files/project-summary-and-fact-sheet.pdf |website=Leiter Reports |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031091213/https://leiterreports.typepad.com/files/project-summary-and-fact-sheet.pdf |archivedate=31 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Two were submitted to ''Hypatia''.<ref name=Weinberg3Oct2018/>\n\nThe first paper, \"The Progressive Stack: An Intersectional Feminist Approach to Pedagogy\", was not accepted; the authors were three times advised to revise and resubmit. The paper suggested that \"educators should discriminate by identity and calculate their students\u2019 status in terms of privilege, favor the least privileged with more time, attention and positive feedback and penalize the most privileged by declining to hear their contributions, deriding their input, intentionally speaking over them, and making them sit on the floor in chains&nbsp;...\"<ref name=Weinberg3Oct2018/> One ''Hypatia'' reviewer reportedly asked how privileged students could be made to \"feel genuinely uncomfortable in ways that are humbling and productive\", but not \"so uncomfortable (shame) that they resist with renewed vigor\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leiter |first1=Brian |author-link=Brian Leiter |title=Sokal Hoax, redux |url=https://leiterreports.typepad.com/blog/2018/10/sokal-hoax-redux.html |website=Leiter Reports |date=3 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=FactSheet/>\n\nThe second paper, \"When the Joke Is on You: A Feminist Perspective on How Positionality Influences Satire\", was accepted.<ref name=Weinberg3Oct2018>{{cite web |last1=Weinberg |first1=Justin |title=Hypatia and other Journals Successfully Tricked Into Accepting 'Fake' Papers (Updated) |url=http://dailynous.com/2018/10/03/hypatia-journals-successfully-tricked-accepting-fake-papers/ |work=Daily Nous |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005085145/http://dailynous.com/2018/10/03/hypatia-journals-successfully-tricked-accepting-fake-papers/ |archivedate=5 October 2018 |date=3 October 2018}}</ref> The paper argued that \"satirical or ironic critique of social justice scholarship are unethical, characterized by ignorance, and rooted in a desire to preserve privilege\", although the same kind of critique would be acceptable in fields such as economics.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mounk|first=Yascha|author-link=Yascha Mounk |title= The Circling of the Academic Wagons |url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/What-the-Grievance/244753 |work=The Chronicle of Higher Education |date=9 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20181101222953/https://www.chronicle.com/article/What-the-Grievance/244753 |archivedate=1 November 2018 |url-status=live}}.</ref><ref name=Weinberg3Oct2018/><ref name=FactSheet/> The ''Wall Street Journal'' exposed the hoax before ''Hypatia'' had published the article.<ref name=Schuessler4Oct2018/>\n\n==Abstracting and indexing==\n''Hypatia'' is [[abstracting and indexing|abstracted and indexed]] in the following [[bibliographic databases]]:<ref>{{cite web<!--Citation bot deny--> |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001/homepage/ProductInformation.html |title=Overview |work=Hypathia |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell}}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=26em|\n*[[Arts and Humanities Citation Index]]<ref name=ISI>{{cite web |url=http://ip-science.thomsonreuters.com/mjl/ |title=Master Journal List |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |work=Intellectual Property & Science |accessdate=2017-07-25}}</ref>\n*[[Current Contents]]/Arts & Humanities<ref name=ISI/>\n*Current Contents/Social & Behavioral Sciences<ref name=ISI/>\n*[[EBSCO Information Services|EBSCO databases]]\n*[[International Bibliography of Periodical Literature]]\n*[[International Political Science Abstracts]]\n*[[MLA International Bibliography]]\n*[[Philosopher's Index]]\n*[[PhilPapers]]\n*[[ProQuest|ProQuest databases]]\n*[[Scopus]] <ref name=Scopus>{{cite web |url=https://www.scopus.com/sourceid/23699 |title=Source details: Hypatia |publisher=[[Elsevier]] |work=Scopus preview |accessdate=2017-07-25}}</ref>\n*[[Social Science Citation Index]]<ref name=ISI/>\n*[[Sociological Abstracts]]\n}}\nAccording to the ''[[Journal Citation Reports]]'', the journal has a 2017 [[impact factor]] of 0.712.<ref name=WoS>{{cite book |year=2018 |chapter=Hypatia |title=2017 Journal Citation Reports |publisher=[[Clarivate Analytics]] |edition=Social Sciences |series=[[Web of Science]]|title-link=Journal Citation Reports }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of women's studies journals]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|26em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Official|http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1527-2001}}\n* {{cite web |title=Editorial and governance boards |url=http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |website=Hypatia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724092156/http://hypatiaphilosophy.org/about/edandgovboards/ |archivedate=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}\n* [[Azizah Y. al-Hibri|Al-Hibri, Azizah Y.]] and Simons, Margaret A. (1990). ''Hypatia Reborn: Essays in Feminist Philosophy''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press.\n* Berm\u00fadez, Jos\u00e9 Luis (5 May 2017). [https://www.insidehighered.com/views/2017/05/05/real-damage-done-flare-over-philosophers-journal-article-essay \"Defining \u2018Harm\u2019 in the Tuvel Affair\"], ''Inside Higher Ed''.\n* Glancy, Josh (7 May 2017). [https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/world/philosopher-lashed-for-backing-transracial-pioneer-ndc0btdjt \"Philosopher lashed for backing \u2018transracial\u2019 pioneer\"], ''The Times''.\n* [[Laurie Shrage|Shrage, Laurie]] (22 May 2017). [http://dailynous.com/2017/05/22/feminist-philosophy-controversies-guest-post-laurie-shrage/ \"Feminist Philosophy and Its Controversies\"], ''Daily Nous''.\n* {{cite news|last1=Walters|first1=Suzanna Danuta|author-link=Suzanna Danuta Walters|title=Academe's Poisonous Call-Out Culture|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Academe-s-Poisonous-Call-Out/240016|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=5 May 2017}}\n*[https://www.ualberta.ca/post-doctoral-fellows-association/news-events/events/arts/1cgp8su5thbt8hajc16e5h7po9 \"Social Justice, Feminist Affects & Philosophical Futures: A Symposium Responding to the Hypatia Controversy\"], University of Alberta, 7 March 2018.\n*[https://www.pdcnet.org/collection-anonymous/browse?fp=philtoday&fq=philtoday%2fVolume%2f8938%7c62%2f8999%7cIssue%3a+1%2f \"Special symposium: Rebecca Tuvel and her interlocutors\"], ''Philosophy Today''. 62(1), Winter 2018.\n\n{{philosophy topics}}\n{{feminism}}\n{{Philosophy journals|state=collapsed}}\n{{portal bar|Feminism|Philosophy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy}}\n[[Category:English-language journals]]\n[[Category:Feminism and society]]\n[[Category:Feminist journals]]\n[[Category:Feminist philosophy]]\n[[Category:Gender studies journals]]\n[[Category:Wiley-Blackwell academic journals]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Philosophy journals]]\n[[Category:Quarterly journals]]\n[[Category:Women's mass media]]\n[[Category:Women's studies journals]]\n", "name_user": "Kleuske", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypatia_(journal)"}
{"title_page": "Jeet Prime", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox TV channel\n|name=Jeet Prime\n|logofile=Jeet_Prime's_logo.png\n|logosize=\n|logoalt=\n|logocaption=\n|launch={{start date|df=yes|2018|02|12}}\n| closed date    = {{start date|df=yes|2020|01|12}}\n|owner=[[Discovery Networks Asia Pacific]]\n|picture format=4:3 ([[576i]], [[SDTV]]) <br>16:9 ([[1080i]], [[HDTV]])\n|slogan=\n|headquarters= [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n|country=India\n|language=[[Hindi]]<br>[[Tamil language|Tamil]]<br>[[Telugu language|Telugu]]<br>[[English language|English]] \n|former names = Discovery  Jeet (2018-2019)\n|replaced names=[[Investigation Discovery (India)|Investigation Discovery]] (original)\n|replaced by names = Investigation Discovery (relaunch)\n|sister names=[[Animal Planet India|Animal Planet]]<br />[[TLC India|TLC]]<br />[[Discovery Turbo]]<br />[[Discovery Kids (India)|Discovery Kids]]<br />[[Discovery Science (India)|Discovery Science]]<br />[[Discovery Channel (India)|Discovery Channel]]<br />[[DSport|Eurosport]]\n|}}\n\n''' Jeet Prime''' was an Indian general entertainment channel launched by [[Discovery Networks Asia Pacific]] on 12 February 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/gecs/not-relying-on-movies-to-garner-jeets-viewership-karan-bajaj-180206|title=Not relying on movies to garner Jeet's viewership: Karan Bajaj|date=2018-02-06|work=Indian Television Dot Com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en}}</ref>.\n\n== History ==\nThe channel replaced [[Investigation Discovery (Indian TV channel)|Investigation Discovery]] on 1 February 2018 and was officially launched on 12 February 2018 as Discovery  Jeet. <ref name=\":0\" /> The company also shifted their headquarters from Delhi to Mumbai which is more suited for building a national general entertainment channel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/p3TPPsBFpoMyl9HhgB1w4M/Karan-Bajaj-A-winning-discovery.html|title=Karan Bajaj: A winning discovery|last=Bansal|first=Shuchi|date=2017-12-22|work=Livemint|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref> It aims to create 1000 hours of original content a year. The shows will also be available digitally via [[Netflix]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe channel had a reach of 140 million on the day of launch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.televisionpost.com/jeet-had-a-reach-of-140-million-on-launch-day-claims-discovery/|title=Jeet had a reach of 140 million on launch day, claims Discovery|website=www.televisionpost.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref> Discovery Jeet is also available on Jio TV app and Airtel TV app.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indianable.com/discovery-jeet-channel-number/|title=Watch Discovery Jeet on Jio TV and Airtel TV|website=www.indianable.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-15}}</ref>\n\nDiscovery announced plans to revamp the channel with dubbed content from [[Scripps Networks Interactive|Scripps]] after low ratings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story/52900_Discovery-to-dub-foreign-content-as-Hindi-GEC-channel-doesnt-stir-viewers|title=Discovery to dub foreign content as Hindi GEC channel doesn't stir viewers|website=www.afaqs.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-08}}</ref>\n\nThe channel was rebranded as Jeet Prime on 1 February 2019. \n\nThe channel was replaced by a relaunched Investigation Discovery on 12 January 2020.<ref name=\"Investigation Discovery Relaunched Replacing Jeet Prime\">{{cite web |title=Investigation Discovery Relaunched Replacing Jeet Prime |url=https://dreamdth.com/community/threads/investigation-discovery-relaunched-replacing-jeet-prime.127565/ |website=DreamDTH |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n==='''Final'''===\nAs of October 2018, channel's new programming with Hindi dubbed content from [[Scripps Networks Interactive|Scripps]]\n\n*[[Cutthroat Kitchen]]\n*[[Toddlers & Tiaras|Toddler's and Tiaras]]\n*[[Guilty Pleasures (TV series)|Guilty Pleasure]]\n*[[90 Day Fianc\u00e9|90 Days Fianc\u00e9]]\n*[[Deadly Women]]\n===Former===\nAs of June 2018, the channel replaced original programming with Hindi dubbed original shows of the [[Investigation Discovery (India)|Investigation Discovery]] channel.<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n* ''[[A Crime to Remember]]''\n* ''[[Cry Wolfe]]''\n* ''[[Deadly Sins (TV Series)|Deadly Sins]]''\n* ''[[Evil Kin]]''\n* ''[[Murder Among Friends (2016 TV series)|Murder Among Friends]]'' \n* ''[[Unraveled (TV series)|Unraveled]]''\n* ''[[The Perfect Murder (TV series)|The Perfect Murder]]''\n* ''[[Tabloid (TV series)|Tabloid]]''\n* ''[[Web of Lies (TV series)|Web of Lies]]''\n\n===Former original programming===\n*''[[21 Sarfarosh - Saragarhi 1897]]''<ref name=\"DiscvoveryJeet\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.televisionpost.com/discovery-jeet-to-cease-original-programming-by-june-end-launch-fresh-intl-content-in-h2-fy19/|title=Discovery Jeet to cease original programming by June-end, launch fresh intl content in H2 FY19|website=www.televisionpost.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n*''[[Anjaan: Special Crimes Unit]]''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''Comedy High School''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''[[Darr Ke Uss Paar]]''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''Gabru: Hip Hop Ke Shehzaade''<ref name=Postt>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/gecs/discovery-jeet-postpones-2-show-launches-to-late-march-180222|title=Discovery Jeet postpones 2 show launches to late March|date=22 February 2018|publisher=Indian Television|accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n*''Khan No.1''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''Man vs Wild with Sunny Leone''<ref name=Postt/>\n*''[[Mere Papa Hero Hiralal]]'' <ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''Shaadi Jasoos''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''[[Swami Ramdev - Ek Sangharsh]]''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n\n== External links ==\n[https://www.facebook.com/DiscoveryJeet Official Facebook page]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Discovery Communications}}\n[[Category:Television stations in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television channels in India]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2020]]\n[[Category:Discovery Networks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox TV channel\n|name=Jeet Prime\n|logofile=Jeet_Prime's_logo.png\n|logosize=\n|logoalt=\n|logocaption=\n|launch={{start date|df=yes|2018|02|12}}\n| closed date    = {{start date|df=yes|2020|01|12}}\n|owner=[[Discovery Networks Asia Pacific]]\n|picture format=4:3 ([[576i]], [[SDTV]]) <br>16:9 ([[1080i]], [[HDTV]])\n|slogan=\n|headquarters= [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n|country=India\n|language=[[Hindi]]<br>[[Tamil language|Tamil]]<br>[[Telugu language|Telugu]]<br>[[English language|English]] \n|former names = Discovery  Jeet (2018-2019)\n|replaced names=[[Investigation Discovery (India)|Investigation Discovery]] (original)\n|replaced by names = Investigation Discovery (relaunch)\n|sister names=[[Animal Planet India|Animal Planet]]<br />[[TLC India|TLC]]<br />[[Discovery Turbo]]<br />[[Discovery Kids (India)|Discovery Kids]]<br />[[Discovery Science (India)|Discovery Science]]<br />[[Discovery Channel (India)|Discovery Channel]]<br />[[DSport|Eurosport]]\n|}}\n\n''' Jeet Prime''' was an Indian general entertainment channel launched by [[Discovery Networks Asia Pacific]] on 12 February 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/gecs/not-relying-on-movies-to-garner-jeets-viewership-karan-bajaj-180206|title=Not relying on movies to garner Jeet's viewership: Karan Bajaj|date=2018-02-06|work=Indian Television Dot Com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en}}</ref>.\n\n== History ==\nThe channel replaced [[Investigation Discovery (Indian TV channel)|Investigation Discovery]] on 1 February 2018 and was officially launched on 12 February 2018 as Discovery  Jeet. <ref name=\":0\" /> The company also shifted their headquarters from Delhi to Mumbai which is more suited for building a national general entertainment channel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/p3TPPsBFpoMyl9HhgB1w4M/Karan-Bajaj-A-winning-discovery.html|title=Karan Bajaj: A winning discovery|last=Bansal|first=Shuchi|date=2017-12-22|work=Livemint|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref> It aims to create 1000 hours of original content a year. The shows will also be available digitally via [[Netflix]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe channel had a reach of 140 million on the day of launch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.televisionpost.com/jeet-had-a-reach-of-140-million-on-launch-day-claims-discovery/|title=Jeet had a reach of 140 million on launch day, claims Discovery|website=www.televisionpost.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref> Discovery Jeet is also available on Jio TV app and Airtel TV app.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indianable.com/discovery-jeet-channel-number/|title=Watch Discovery Jeet on Jio TV and Airtel TV|website=www.indianable.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-15}}</ref>\n\nDiscovery announced plans to revamp the channel with dubbed content from [[Scripps Networks Interactive|Scripps]] after low ratings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story/52900_Discovery-to-dub-foreign-content-as-Hindi-GEC-channel-doesnt-stir-viewers|title=Discovery to dub foreign content as Hindi GEC channel doesn't stir viewers|website=www.afaqs.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-08}}</ref>\n\nThe channel was rebranded as Jeet Prime on 1 February 2019. \n\nThe channel was replaced by a relaunched Investigation Discovery on 12 January 2020.<ref name=\"Investigation Discovery Relaunched Replacing Jeet Prime\">{{cite web |title=Investigation Discovery Relaunched Replacing Jeet Prime |url=https://dreamdth.com/community/threads/investigation-discovery-relaunched-replacing-jeet-prime.127565/ |website=DreamDTH |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n==='''Final'''===\nAs of October 2018, channel's new programming with Hindi dubbed content from [[Scripps Networks Interactive|Scripps]]\n\n*[[Cutthroat Kitchen]]\n*[[Toddlers & Tiaras|Toddler's and Tiaras]]\n*[[Guilty Pleasures (TV series)|Guilty Pleasure]]\n*[[90 Day Fianc\u00e9|90 Days Fianc\u00e9]]\n*[[Deadly Women]]\n===Former===\nAs of June 2018, the channel replaced original programming with Hindi dubbed original shows of the [[Investigation Discovery (India)|Investigation Discovery]] channel.<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n* ''[[A Crime to Remember]]''\n* ''[[Cry Wolfe]]''\n* ''[[Deadly Sins (TV Series)|Deadly Sins]]''\n* ''[[Evil Kin]]''\n* ''[[Murder Among Friends (2016 TV series)|Murder Among Friends]]'' \n* ''[[Unraveled (TV series)|Unraveled]]''\n* ''[[The Perfect Murder (TV series)|The Perfect Murder]]''\n* ''[[Tabloid (TV series)|Tabloid]]''\n* ''[[Web of Lies (TV series)|Web of Lies]]''\n\n===Former original programming===\n*''[[21 Sarfarosh - Saragarhi 1897]]''<ref name=\"DiscvoveryJeet\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.televisionpost.com/discovery-jeet-to-cease-original-programming-by-june-end-launch-fresh-intl-content-in-h2-fy19/|title=Discovery Jeet to cease original programming by June-end, launch fresh intl content in H2 FY19|website=www.televisionpost.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n*''[[Anjaan: Special Crimes Unit]]''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''Comedy High School''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''[[Darr Ke Uss Paar]]''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''Gabru: Hip Hop Ke Shehzaade''<ref name=Postt>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/gecs/discovery-jeet-postpones-2-show-launches-to-late-march-180222|title=Discovery Jeet postpones 2 show launches to late March|date=22 February 2018|publisher=Indian Television|accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n*''Khan No.1''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''Man vs Wild with Sunny Leone''<ref name=Postt/>\n*''[[Mere Papa Hero Hiralal]]'' <ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''Shaadi Jasoos''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n*''[[Swami Ramdev - Ek Sangharsh]]''<ref name=DiscvoveryJeet/>\n\n== External links ==\n[https://www.facebook.com/DiscoveryJeet Official Facebook page]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Discovery Communications}}\n[[Category:Television stations in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television channels in India]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Television channels and disstations established in 2020]]\n[[Category:Discovery Networks]]\n", "name_user": "E789999", "label": "safe", "comment": "Forgot somethin'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeet_Prime"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Guam}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam\n| map1            = \n| places          = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Guam]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = March 15, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=15|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 135<ref name=\"DPHSS_COVID-19\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) |url=http://dphss.guam.gov/covid-19/ |website=Guam Deparment of Public Health and Social Services}}</ref><ref name=\"Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center\">{{cite web |last1=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine |title=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center Map |url=https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/ |website=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center |publisher=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 66<ref name=\"DPHSS_COVID-19\"/>\n| deaths          = 5<ref name=\"DPHSS_COVID-19\"/><ref name=\"Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center\" />\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [http://dphss.guam.gov/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-n-cov/ Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the United States territory of [[Guam]] on March 15, 2020. As of April 14, 2020, there are 135 confirmed cases and five deaths.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness  in [[Wuhan City]], Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref> Unlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" />\n\nTourism from East Asian countries is a pillar of Guam's economy. In December 2019, there were 67,000 visitors from Japan (first confirmed COVID-19 case on 15 January) and 71,000 from South Korea (first case 20 January). Visitors from the US, Taiwan, Philippines, and China made up less than 10% of December 2019 arrivals.<ref>{{cite web |title=December 2019 Arrivals |url=https://www.guamvisitorsbureau.com/docs/research/statistics/visitor-arrival-statistics/fy-2020/december-2019-preliminary-arrival-summary.pdf |website=Guam Visitors Bureau |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> In comparison, the total population of Guam is about 165,000.\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February 2020 ===\n\n* February 7, 2020: The [[Government of Guam]] denied the entry request by the cruise ship {{MS|Westerdam}}, which had potentially infected passengers.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Guam COVID-19 Joint Information Center |title=Administration Denies Entry of Potentially-Infected Vessel |url=http://dphss.guam.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/JIC_2_7_2020-1.pdf |website=Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n* March 9: The [[Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services]] received its first COVID-19 test kits from the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Guam COVID-19 Joint Information Center |title=DPHSS Guam Public Health Laboratory Works to Validate Results of Newly Arrived COVID-19 Test Kits; No Suspect or Confirmed Cases |url=http://dphss.guam.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/News-Release-DPHSS-Guam-Public-Health-Laboratory-Works-to-Validate-Results-of-Newly-Arrived-COVID-19-Test-Kits_-No-Suspect-or-Confirmed-Cases.pdf.pdf |website=Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 13: [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]] began checking arrivals for fever.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/weeks-after-covid--outbreaks-guam-airport-starts-fever-scans/video_c593acac-64c0-11ea-a456-7ff8e41c1f02.html |title=Weeks after COVID-19 outbreaks, Guam airport starts fever scans |work=The Guam Daily Post |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 15: The first three cases of [[COVID-19]] in the territory were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Anumita|last=Kaur|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/15/governor-3-guam-confirmed-positive-covid-19/5053098002/ |title=Governor: 3 on Guam confirmed positive for COVID-19|website=Pacific Daily News |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n*:The Mayors' Council of Guam suspended all [[Villages of Guam|village]]-sponsored events and activities. It was announced that public senior citizen centers would close on March 18. [[Guam Memorial Hospital]] restricted its emergency department to staff and patients only.<ref name=JIC_031520>{{cite web |author1=Guam COVID-19 Joint Information Center |title=GMHA Visitor Policy Changes; Mayors Council Suspends All Village Events |url=http://dphss.guam.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/JIC-Release-No.-2-GMHA-Visitor-Policy-Changes-Mayors-Council-Suspends-All-Village-Events-1.pdf-1.pdf |website=Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 16: Public schools closed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Limtiaco |first1=Steve |title=COVID-19 impact: No word yet on what happens to this year's graduating class |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/18/coronavirus-guam-update-covid-19-department-education-impact-graduation/5075978002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*: Gathering of 50 or more people in a single room prohibited. Arriving travelers from areas affected by COVID-19 subject to mandatory quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gatherings of more than 50 prohibited; mandatory quarantine for some travelers |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/16/gatherings-50-prohibited-mandatory-quarantine-some-travelers/5056375002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 17: [[Naval Base Guam]] and [[Andersen Air Force Base]] closed on-base programs and limited base access.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sablan |first1=Jerick |title=Guam military bases close programs, limit access in response to COVID-19 |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/17/guam-military-bases-close-programs-limit-access/5063662002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Department of Defense Education Activity|Defense Department schools]] were closed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ornauer |first1=Dave |title=DODEA schools on Guam to close amid coronavirus public health emergency |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/dodea-schools-on-guam-to-close-amid-coronavirus-public-health-emergency-1.622657 |website=Stars and Stripes |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 20: Governor [[Lou Leon Guerrero]]'s executive order shuts down nonessential businesses and gatherings. The same day, [[Japan Airlines]] announced flights from [[Narita Airport]] would be suspended until April 24.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaur |first1=Anumita |title=Guam seeks federal relief as shut down goes in effect and closures, cancellations continue |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/money/2020/03/21/guam-seeks-federal-relief-shut-down-effect-and-closures-continue/2882293001/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Pacific Daily News |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Guam_National_Guard_-_49694586463.jpg|thumb|[[Guam Army National Guard]]sman at a COVID-19 isolation site, March 22]]\n* March 22: The Governor of Guam declares a State of Emergency.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guam State of Emergency Declaration Order |url=https://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/emergency/guam-state-emergency-declaration-order |website=www.fmcsa.dot.gov |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n*:The territory's first death from the virus, a 68-year-old woman with \"multiple [[co-morbidities]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Guam confirms Pacific's first Covid-19 death |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412328/coronavirus-guam-confirms-pacific-s-first-covid-19-death |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=RNZ |date=22 March 2020 |language=en-nz}}</ref>\n* March 25: Four sailors with COVID-19 evacuated from {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} and flown to Naval Base Guam for treatment.<ref>{{cite web |title=4 sailors with COVID-19 evacuated from USS Theodore Roosevelt to Guam |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/25/4-sailors-covid-19-evacuated-uss-theodore-roosevelt-guam/5076608002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''(See [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]].)''\n* March 26: The [[University of Guam]] announced that all classes were moving to an online or alternate format for the remainder of the spring semester. The university planned to complete the semester on its current schedule.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Daily Post Staff |title=UOG classes going online for semester |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/uog-classes-going-online-for-semester/article_ab6c7f7c-6f27-11ea-a365-bb1c1b15e4c4.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |publisher=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*:USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' docked at Naval Base Guam due to an outbreak on board.<ref name=\"NBC Gains Griffith\">{{cite news |last1=Gains |first1=Mosheh |last2=Griffith |first2=Janelle |title=Coronavirus outbreak diverts Navy aircraft carrier to Guam, all 5,000 aboard to be tested |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-diverts-navy-aircraft-carrier-guam-all-5-000-n1169726 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=NBC News |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 27: The territory had confirmed 45 positive COVID-19 cases out of 308 total tests.<ref name=\"45 of 308 test positive for COVID-19: The Guam Daily Post\">{{cite web |last1=Delgado |first1=Nick |title='There are tough days ahead': 45 of 308 test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/there-are-tough-days-ahead/article_de77a7a4-6f20-11ea-867e-ab53e1e2b25b.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |publisher=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 28: [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] approved a disaster declaration for Guam that orders Federal assistance to supplement territory and local coronavirus recovery efforts.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/president-donald-j-trump-approves-guam-disaster-declaration-3/|title=President Donald J. Trump Approves Guam Disaster Declaration|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The President also signed the national $2 trillion COVID-19 relief bill with approximately $111 million allocated to Guam.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* March 31: The Governor's Press Secretary Krystal Paco-San Agustin confirmed two new cases of the coronavirus. Guam's Public Health Lab had tested 20 samples with the remaining 18 coming back negative.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two more Covid-19 cases in Guam |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/413025/two-more-covid-19-cases-in-guam |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n[[File:Guam National Guard - 49695431352.jpg|thumb|The [[Guam Air National Guard]] assisting Guam police at an isolation facility. The Guam National Guard was activated by Gov. [[Lou Leon Guerrero]] on March 21 to assist with COVID-19 efforts.]]\n* April 4: The government projected that with a 20% reduction in spread, COVID-19 would kill 3,000 people in five months. The population of Guam is approximately 160,000 - indicating that COVID-19 would kill about 1.8% of the territory in five months. The governor urged the populace to reduce the rate of spread.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sablan |first1=Jerick |title=Governor announces stricter COVID-19 measures to enforce stay home orders |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/03/governor-announces-stricter-measures-enforce-stay-home-orders/5119099002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> \n*: Governor Leon Guerrero announced that residents would be prohibited from driving for non-essential reasons from April 7. Road checkpoints would be manned by police and the Guam National Guard.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Delgado |first1=Nick |title=Governor: Road checkpoints start Tuesday |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/governor-road-checkpoints-start-tuesday/article_6d8b659c-7571-11ea-8297-9fe448f2368d.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> Residents rushed  to stores and banks before the restrictions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lloyd |first1=Bruce |title=Coronavirus on Guam: Banks, stores busy ahead of new restrictions |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/money/2020/04/06/covid-19-guam-streets-busy-pending-new-coronavirus-restrictions/2952660001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n*:The Navy announced that they had secured agreement to quarantine about 3,000 sailors from USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' in local hotel rooms.<ref>{{cite web |title=Navy: 3,000 sailors will be housed in Guam hotels |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/navy-3-000-sailors-will-be-housed-in-guam-hotels/article_f18a44fc-759f-11ea-bc17-9b28e21c7b29.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 5: The Public Health Emergency was extended until May 5.<ref name=PDN_050420>{{cite web |last1=Kaur |first1=Anumita |title=Governor extends public health emergency to May 5; residents' travel not restricted yet |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/05/governor-extends-public-health-emergency-may-5/2949673001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=en |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> \n*:An executive order authorized extra pay for government workers based on their potential exposure to the virus; the maximum of an additional 25% was reserved for law enforcement, health care providers, and others with direct contact with likely infected members of the public.<ref name=PDN_050420/> \n*:GovGuam announced that the military would be contributing 30 ventilators to local efforts.<ref name=PDN_050420/>\n* April 6: The [[Guam Department of Education]] Superintendent officially canceled classes for the remainder of the school year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Limticao |first1=Steve |title=Superintendent Jon Fernandez cancels classes for rest of school year |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/2020/04/05/guam-department-education-superintendent-jon-fernandez-cancels-rest-school-year/2952618001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 7: It was reported that most of Guam's positive cases had tracked epidemiological links to other known cases.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Santo Thomas |first1=Jojo |title=Eight test positive for COVID-19, Guam total at 121 |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/07/eight-test-positive-covid-19-guam-total-121/2959798001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 9: GovGuam cleared land for an additional 500 plots at the island's public cemetery in anticipation of future COVID-19 casualties.  GovGuam has also temporarily waived the $500 burial fee at Vicente A. Limtiaco Memorial Cemetery in [[Piti, Guam|Piti]]. The director of the [[Guam Department of Parks and Recreation]] stated, \"We're all praying the surge doesn\u2019t happen.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Limtiaco |first1=Steve |title=Government adds hundreds of gravesites in case of large coronavirus death toll |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/2020/04/09/covid-19-guam-govguam-expands-cemetery-case-large-death-toll/5120125002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 10: Governor Leon Guerrero announced the closure of designated road lanes, where traffic will be funneled into chokepoints and National Guardsmen will ask drivers about the purpose of their trip. These can no longer be referred to as \"checkpoints,\" as the [[Attorney General of Guam]] has advised that the government does not have the authority to create disease checkpoints.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Limtiaco |first1=Steve |title=Governor orders daily road closures to deter non-essential travel |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/10/governor-orders-daily-road-closures-deter-non-essential-travel/5128709002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=10 April 2020 |language=en |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 12: The University of Guam announced that it was delivering almost 300 meals daily to health care workers and volunteers at Department of Public Health and Social Services sites. The food was donated from various restaurants, wholesalers, organizations, and individuals, with any bulk food prepared by restaurant and catering business Nayon Express, before being delivered by UOG staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=UOG delivers thousands of meals to front line workers |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/11/university-workers-deliver-thousands-meals-front-line-workers/5128036002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 13: A sailor from USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' died.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warship sailor dies of COVID-19 |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/warship-sailor-dies-of-covid-19/article_4e09ae96-7d86-11ea-bfc9-97a147194fea.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*:[[Joint Region Marianas]] Commander Rear Adm. John Menoni announced that a sailor from USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' had broken quarantine in the local hotel that they were located within and an investigation was ongoing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sablan |first1=Jerick |title=Rear Admiral: Sailor under investigation for not following quarantine protocol |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/13/admiral-sailor-under-investigation-not-following-quarantine-protocol/2980896001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n*:Gov. Leon Guerrero urged the [[Legislature of Guam]] to pass bills that would allow her to set a curfew and create checkpoints with penalties.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaur |first1=Anumita |title=Bills for social distancing enforcement still stalled; governor says she needs that power |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/13/social-distancing-enforcement-bills-stalled-governor-needs-power/2980910001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Guam medical cases chart}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)| 2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' (CVN-71)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Guam}}\n* [http://dphss.guam.gov/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-n-cov/ Coronavirus information] from [[Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Guam|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in insular areas of the United States|Guam]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania|Guam]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Guam]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Guam}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam\n| map1            = \n| places          = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Guam]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = March 15, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=15|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 135<ref name=\"DPHSS_COVID-19\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) |url=http://dphss.guam.gov/covid-19/ |website=Guam Deparment of Public Health and Social Services}}</ref><ref name=\"Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center\">{{cite web |last1=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine |title=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center Map |url=https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/ |website=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center |publisher=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 66<ref name=\"DPHSS_COVID-19\"/>\n| deaths          = 5<ref name=\"DPHSS_COVID-19\"/><ref name=\"Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center\" />\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [http://dphss.guam.gov/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-n-cov/ Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the United States territory of [[Guam]] on March 15, 2020. As of April 14, 2020, there are 135 confirmed cases and six deaths.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness  in [[Wuhan City]], Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref> Unlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" />\n\nTourism from East Asian countries is a pillar of Guam's economy. In December 2019, there were 67,000 visitors from Japan (first confirmed COVID-19 case on 15 January) and 71,000 from South Korea (first case 20 January). Visitors from the US, Taiwan, Philippines, and China made up less than 10% of December 2019 arrivals.<ref>{{cite web |title=December 2019 Arrivals |url=https://www.guamvisitorsbureau.com/docs/research/statistics/visitor-arrival-statistics/fy-2020/december-2019-preliminary-arrival-summary.pdf |website=Guam Visitors Bureau |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> In comparison, the total population of Guam is about 165,000.\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February 2020 ===\n\n* February 7, 2020: The [[Government of Guam]] denied the entry request by the cruise ship {{MS|Westerdam}}, which had potentially infected passengers.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Guam COVID-19 Joint Information Center |title=Administration Denies Entry of Potentially-Infected Vessel |url=http://dphss.guam.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/JIC_2_7_2020-1.pdf |website=Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n* March 9: The [[Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services]] received its first COVID-19 test kits from the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Guam COVID-19 Joint Information Center |title=DPHSS Guam Public Health Laboratory Works to Validate Results of Newly Arrived COVID-19 Test Kits; No Suspect or Confirmed Cases |url=http://dphss.guam.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/News-Release-DPHSS-Guam-Public-Health-Laboratory-Works-to-Validate-Results-of-Newly-Arrived-COVID-19-Test-Kits_-No-Suspect-or-Confirmed-Cases.pdf.pdf |website=Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 13: [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]] began checking arrivals for fever.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/weeks-after-covid--outbreaks-guam-airport-starts-fever-scans/video_c593acac-64c0-11ea-a456-7ff8e41c1f02.html |title=Weeks after COVID-19 outbreaks, Guam airport starts fever scans |work=The Guam Daily Post |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 15: The first three cases of [[COVID-19]] in the territory were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Anumita|last=Kaur|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/15/governor-3-guam-confirmed-positive-covid-19/5053098002/ |title=Governor: 3 on Guam confirmed positive for COVID-19|website=Pacific Daily News |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n*:The Mayors' Council of Guam suspended all [[Villages of Guam|village]]-sponsored events and activities. It was announced that public senior citizen centers would close on March 18. [[Guam Memorial Hospital]] restricted its emergency department to staff and patients only.<ref name=JIC_031520>{{cite web |author1=Guam COVID-19 Joint Information Center |title=GMHA Visitor Policy Changes; Mayors Council Suspends All Village Events |url=http://dphss.guam.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/JIC-Release-No.-2-GMHA-Visitor-Policy-Changes-Mayors-Council-Suspends-All-Village-Events-1.pdf-1.pdf |website=Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 16: Public schools closed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Limtiaco |first1=Steve |title=COVID-19 impact: No word yet on what happens to this year's graduating class |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/18/coronavirus-guam-update-covid-19-department-education-impact-graduation/5075978002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*: Gathering of 50 or more people in a single room prohibited. Arriving travelers from areas affected by COVID-19 subject to mandatory quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gatherings of more than 50 prohibited; mandatory quarantine for some travelers |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/16/gatherings-50-prohibited-mandatory-quarantine-some-travelers/5056375002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 17: [[Naval Base Guam]] and [[Andersen Air Force Base]] closed on-base programs and limited base access.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sablan |first1=Jerick |title=Guam military bases close programs, limit access in response to COVID-19 |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/17/guam-military-bases-close-programs-limit-access/5063662002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[Department of Defense Education Activity|Defense Department schools]] were closed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ornauer |first1=Dave |title=DODEA schools on Guam to close amid coronavirus public health emergency |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/dodea-schools-on-guam-to-close-amid-coronavirus-public-health-emergency-1.622657 |website=Stars and Stripes |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 20: Governor [[Lou Leon Guerrero]]'s executive order shuts down nonessential businesses and gatherings. The same day, [[Japan Airlines]] announced flights from [[Narita Airport]] would be suspended until April 24.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaur |first1=Anumita |title=Guam seeks federal relief as shut down goes in effect and closures, cancellations continue |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/money/2020/03/21/guam-seeks-federal-relief-shut-down-effect-and-closures-continue/2882293001/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Pacific Daily News |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Guam_National_Guard_-_49694586463.jpg|thumb|[[Guam Army National Guard]]sman at a COVID-19 isolation site, March 22]]\n* March 22: The Governor of Guam declares a State of Emergency.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guam State of Emergency Declaration Order |url=https://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/emergency/guam-state-emergency-declaration-order |website=www.fmcsa.dot.gov |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n*:The territory's first death from the virus, a 68-year-old woman with \"multiple [[co-morbidities]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Guam confirms Pacific's first Covid-19 death |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412328/coronavirus-guam-confirms-pacific-s-first-covid-19-death |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=RNZ |date=22 March 2020 |language=en-nz}}</ref>\n* March 25: Four sailors with COVID-19 evacuated from {{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71|6}} and flown to Naval Base Guam for treatment.<ref>{{cite web |title=4 sailors with COVID-19 evacuated from USS Theodore Roosevelt to Guam |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/25/4-sailors-covid-19-evacuated-uss-theodore-roosevelt-guam/5076608002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''(See [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)]].)''\n* March 26: The [[University of Guam]] announced that all classes were moving to an online or alternate format for the remainder of the spring semester. The university planned to complete the semester on its current schedule.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Daily Post Staff |title=UOG classes going online for semester |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/uog-classes-going-online-for-semester/article_ab6c7f7c-6f27-11ea-a365-bb1c1b15e4c4.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |publisher=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*:USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' docked at Naval Base Guam due to an outbreak on board.<ref name=\"NBC Gains Griffith\">{{cite news |last1=Gains |first1=Mosheh |last2=Griffith |first2=Janelle |title=Coronavirus outbreak diverts Navy aircraft carrier to Guam, all 5,000 aboard to be tested |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-outbreak-diverts-navy-aircraft-carrier-guam-all-5-000-n1169726 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=NBC News |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 27: The territory had confirmed 45 positive COVID-19 cases out of 308 total tests.<ref name=\"45 of 308 test positive for COVID-19: The Guam Daily Post\">{{cite web |last1=Delgado |first1=Nick |title='There are tough days ahead': 45 of 308 test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/there-are-tough-days-ahead/article_de77a7a4-6f20-11ea-867e-ab53e1e2b25b.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |publisher=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 28: [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] approved a disaster declaration for Guam that orders Federal assistance to supplement territory and local coronavirus recovery efforts.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/president-donald-j-trump-approves-guam-disaster-declaration-3/|title=President Donald J. Trump Approves Guam Disaster Declaration|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The President also signed the national $2 trillion COVID-19 relief bill with approximately $111 million allocated to Guam.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* March 31: The Governor's Press Secretary Krystal Paco-San Agustin confirmed two new cases of the coronavirus. Guam's Public Health Lab had tested 20 samples with the remaining 18 coming back negative.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two more Covid-19 cases in Guam |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/413025/two-more-covid-19-cases-in-guam |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n[[File:Guam National Guard - 49695431352.jpg|thumb|The [[Guam Air National Guard]] assisting Guam police at an isolation facility. The Guam National Guard was activated by Gov. [[Lou Leon Guerrero]] on March 21 to assist with COVID-19 efforts.]]\n* April 4: The government projected that with a 20% reduction in spread, COVID-19 would kill 3,000 people in five months. The population of Guam is approximately 160,000 - indicating that COVID-19 would kill about 1.8% of the territory in five months. The governor urged the populace to reduce the rate of spread.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sablan |first1=Jerick |title=Governor announces stricter COVID-19 measures to enforce stay home orders |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/03/governor-announces-stricter-measures-enforce-stay-home-orders/5119099002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> \n*: Governor Leon Guerrero announced that residents would be prohibited from driving for non-essential reasons from April 7. Road checkpoints would be manned by police and the Guam National Guard.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Delgado |first1=Nick |title=Governor: Road checkpoints start Tuesday |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/governor-road-checkpoints-start-tuesday/article_6d8b659c-7571-11ea-8297-9fe448f2368d.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=4 April 2020}}</ref> Residents rushed  to stores and banks before the restrictions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lloyd |first1=Bruce |title=Coronavirus on Guam: Banks, stores busy ahead of new restrictions |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/money/2020/04/06/covid-19-guam-streets-busy-pending-new-coronavirus-restrictions/2952660001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n*:The Navy announced that they had secured agreement to quarantine about 3,000 sailors from USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' in local hotel rooms.<ref>{{cite web |title=Navy: 3,000 sailors will be housed in Guam hotels |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/navy-3-000-sailors-will-be-housed-in-guam-hotels/article_f18a44fc-759f-11ea-bc17-9b28e21c7b29.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 5: The Public Health Emergency was extended until May 5.<ref name=PDN_050420>{{cite web |last1=Kaur |first1=Anumita |title=Governor extends public health emergency to May 5; residents' travel not restricted yet |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/05/governor-extends-public-health-emergency-may-5/2949673001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=en |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> \n*:An executive order authorized extra pay for government workers based on their potential exposure to the virus; the maximum of an additional 25% was reserved for law enforcement, health care providers, and others with direct contact with likely infected members of the public.<ref name=PDN_050420/> \n*:GovGuam announced that the military would be contributing 30 ventilators to local efforts.<ref name=PDN_050420/>\n* April 6: The [[Guam Department of Education]] Superintendent officially canceled classes for the remainder of the school year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Limticao |first1=Steve |title=Superintendent Jon Fernandez cancels classes for rest of school year |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/2020/04/05/guam-department-education-superintendent-jon-fernandez-cancels-rest-school-year/2952618001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 7: It was reported that most of Guam's positive cases had tracked epidemiological links to other known cases.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Santo Thomas |first1=Jojo |title=Eight test positive for COVID-19, Guam total at 121 |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/07/eight-test-positive-covid-19-guam-total-121/2959798001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 9: GovGuam cleared land for an additional 500 plots at the island's public cemetery in anticipation of future COVID-19 casualties.  GovGuam has also temporarily waived the $500 burial fee at Vicente A. Limtiaco Memorial Cemetery in [[Piti, Guam|Piti]]. The director of the [[Guam Department of Parks and Recreation]] stated, \"We're all praying the surge doesn\u2019t happen.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Limtiaco |first1=Steve |title=Government adds hundreds of gravesites in case of large coronavirus death toll |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/2020/04/09/covid-19-guam-govguam-expands-cemetery-case-large-death-toll/5120125002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=en |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 10: Governor Leon Guerrero announced the closure of designated road lanes, where traffic will be funneled into chokepoints and National Guardsmen will ask drivers about the purpose of their trip. These can no longer be referred to as \"checkpoints,\" as the [[Attorney General of Guam]] has advised that the government does not have the authority to create disease checkpoints.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Limtiaco |first1=Steve |title=Governor orders daily road closures to deter non-essential travel |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/10/governor-orders-daily-road-closures-deter-non-essential-travel/5128709002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=10 April 2020 |language=en |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 12: The University of Guam announced that it was delivering almost 300 meals daily to health care workers and volunteers at Department of Public Health and Social Services sites. The food was donated from various restaurants, wholesalers, organizations, and individuals, with any bulk food prepared by restaurant and catering business Nayon Express, before being delivered by UOG staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=UOG delivers thousands of meals to front line workers |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/11/university-workers-deliver-thousands-meals-front-line-workers/5128036002/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 13: A sailor from USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' died.<ref>{{cite web |title=Warship sailor dies of COVID-19 |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/warship-sailor-dies-of-covid-19/article_4e09ae96-7d86-11ea-bfc9-97a147194fea.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n*:[[Joint Region Marianas]] Commander Rear Adm. John Menoni announced that a sailor from USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' had broken quarantine in the local hotel that they were located within and an investigation was ongoing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sablan |first1=Jerick |title=Rear Admiral: Sailor under investigation for not following quarantine protocol |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/13/admiral-sailor-under-investigation-not-following-quarantine-protocol/2980896001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n*:Gov. Leon Guerrero urged the [[Legislature of Guam]] to pass bills that would allow her to set a curfew and create checkpoints with penalties.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaur |first1=Anumita |title=Bills for social distancing enforcement still stalled; governor says she needs that power |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/04/13/social-distancing-enforcement-bills-stalled-governor-needs-power/2980910001/ |website=Pacific Daily News |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Guam medical cases chart}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)| 2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'' (CVN-71)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Guam}}\n* [http://dphss.guam.gov/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-n-cov/ Coronavirus information] from [[Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Guam|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in insular areas of the United States|Guam]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania|Guam]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Guam]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "CAWylie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Guam"}
{"title_page": "Bohmong Circle", "text_new": "{{Bengal Zamindars series}}\n\n[[File:Bandarban Marmas with Bohmong in centre.png|thumb|Group of Bandarban Marmas (Maghs) with Bohmong in centre, c. 1906]]\n\nThe '''Bohmong Circle''' ({{lang-my|\u1017\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a\u1019\u1004\u103a\u1038\u1011\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a}}) is one of three hereditary chiefdoms (or \"circles\") in the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]] of modern-day [[Bangladesh]]. The jurisdiction of the Bohmong Circle encompasses parts of [[Bandarban District]]. The chiefdom's members are of [[Marma people|Marma descent]] and are known as ''ragraisa''.<ref name=\":0\" /> Most inhabitants of the Mong Circle settled in the south during a migration wave from the [[Kingdom of Mrauk U]] (modern-day [[Arakan State]] in [[Myanmar]]) between the 16th and 18th centuries, while inhabitants of the other Marma chiefdom, the [[Mong Circle]], settled in the northwest and are known as ''phalansa'' (\u1016\u101c\u1036\u101e\u102c\u1038).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=|title=Nationalism and Intra-State Conflicts in the Postcolonial World|last=I|first=Fonkem Achankeng|date=2015-09-28|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=9781498500265|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\nThe Bohmong Circle is led by a hereditary chieftain called a \"raja.\" The Bohmong chieftains appoint and oversee headmen called ''mouza'' and village chiefs called ''karbaris''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-71831|title=Saching Prue new Mong King|date=2009-01-18|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> The incumbent chieftain is [[Aung Shwe Prue|Chaw Prue]] (\u1001\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1016\u103c\u1030), an engineer by training.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/raj-punnah-begins-december-21-1323697|title=Raj Punnah begins December 21|date=2016-12-02|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> The Bohmong chieftain leads an annual three-day festival called \"raj punnah,\" which has been held since 1875.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/raj-punnah-begins-dec-21-1495024|title=Raj Punnah begins Dec 21|date=2017-11-23|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/full-implementation-during-govt-1508530|title=Full implementation during this govt|date=2017-12-22|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/raj-punnah-fest-begins-hills-189367|title=Raj Punnah fest begins in hills|date=2015-12-19|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> The Bohmong chieftain also sits on the Advisory Council for the [[Ministry of Chittagong Hill Tracts Affairs]] and the [[Bandarban Hill District Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peaceaccords.nd.edu/sites/default/files/accords/Chittagong_Hill_Tracts_Peace_Accord.pdf|title=Chittagong Hill Tracts Peace Accord|date=1997-12-02}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Bohmong chieftains claim descent from [[Tabinshwehti]] and [[Nanda Bayin]] of the [[First Toungoo Empire|Toungoo Empire]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lostfootsteps.org/en/history/the-history-of-raja-of-the-bohmong-circle|title=The history of Raja of the Bohmong Circle|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.horniman.ac.uk/get_involved/blog/five-go-collecting-kingly-swords|title=Five Go Collecting: Kingly Swords|last=Gardens|first=The Horniman Museum and|website=Horniman Museum and Gardens|language=en|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref> During British rule, the Chittagong Hill Tracts were administratively divided into three circles in 1884, namely the [[Chakma Circle]], the Bohmong Circle, and the [[Mong Circle]]<nowiki/>s, each presided over by a hereditary chief from the [[Chakma people|Chakma]] and [[Marma people]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GZtEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PR17&dq=bohmong+circle#v=onepage&q=bohmong%20circle&f=false|title=An Account of the Chittagong Hill Tracts|last=Hutchinson|first=Robert Henry Sneyd|date=1906|publisher=Bengal Secretariat Book Depot|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite report |last=Kundu|first=Debasish |last2=Samadder|first2=Mrinmoy |last3=Khan|first3=Ashrafuzzaman |last4=Shajahan Naomi|first4=Sharin |date=2011-01-04 |title=State of Justice in Chittagong Hill Tracts: Exploring the Formal and Informal Justice Institutions of Indigenous Communities |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281294250 |publisher=BRAC}}</ref> The circles were codified into law with the Chittagong Hill Tract Regulations, 1900, eased revenue collection and administrative burdens on British authorities by delegating tax collection, land administration management and social arbitration responsibilities to the chieftains.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-121974|title=Bandarban wears festive look as Rajpunyah starts|date=2010-01-15|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 1901, the Bohmong Circle extended {{Convert|2064|mi2|km2}}.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GZtEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA122&dq=hathi+linga#v=snippet&q=mong%20circle&f=false|title=An Account of the Chittagong Hill Tracts|last=Hutchinson|first=Robert Henry Sneyd|date=1906|publisher=Bengal Secretariat Book Depot|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> This administrative structure remained in place until 1964, when the introduction of local self-government abolished the special status of these circles and brought local administration under the control of the central government.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zaman|first=M. Q.|date=1982|title=Crisis in Chittagong Hill Tracts: Ethnicity and Integration|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=17|issue=3|pages=75\u201380|jstor=4370578}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bengal Zamindars}}\n\n[[Category:Bandarban District]]\n[[Category:Dynasties of India]]\n[[Category:Subdivisions of British India]]\n[[Category:History of Bengal]]\n[[Category:Quasi-princely estates of India]]\n[[Category:Lands inhabited by indigenous peoples]]\n[[Category:History of Chittagong Division]]\n", "text_old": "{{Bengal Zamindars series}}\n\n[[File:Bandarban Marmas with Bohmong in centre.png|thumb|Group of Bandarban Marmas (Maghs) with Bohmong in centre, c. 1906]]\n\nThe '''Bohmong Circle''' ({{lang-my|\u1017\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a\u1019\u1004\u103a\u1038\u1011\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a}}) is one of three hereditary chiefdoms (or \"circles\") in the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]] of modern-day [[Bangladesh]]. The jurisdiction of the Bohmong Circle encompasses parts of [[Bandarban District]]. The chiefdom's members are of [[Marma people|Marma descent]] and are known as ''ragraisa''.<ref name=\":0\" /> Most inhabitants of the Mong Circle settled in the south during a migration wave from the [[Kingdom of Mrauk U]] (modern-day [[Arakan State]] in [[Myanmar]]) between the 16th and 18th centuries, while inhabitants of the other Marma chiefdom, the [[Mong Circle]] settled in the northwest and are known as ''phalansa'' (\u1016\u101c\u1036\u101e\u102c\u1038).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=|title=Nationalism and Intra-State Conflicts in the Postcolonial World|last=I|first=Fonkem Achankeng|date=2015-09-28|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=9781498500265|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\nThe Bohmong Circle is led by a hereditary chieftain called a \"raja.\" The Bohmong chieftains appoint and oversee headmen called ''mouza'' and village chiefs called ''karbaris''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-71831|title=Saching Prue new Mong King|date=2009-01-18|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> The incumbent chieftain is [[Aung Shwe Prue|Chaw Prue]] (\u1001\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1016\u103c\u1030), an engineer by training.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/raj-punnah-begins-december-21-1323697|title=Raj Punnah begins December 21|date=2016-12-02|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> The Bohmong chieftain leads an annual three-day festival called \"raj punnah,\" which has been held since 1875.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/raj-punnah-begins-dec-21-1495024|title=Raj Punnah begins Dec 21|date=2017-11-23|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/full-implementation-during-govt-1508530|title=Full implementation during this govt|date=2017-12-22|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/raj-punnah-fest-begins-hills-189367|title=Raj Punnah fest begins in hills|date=2015-12-19|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref> The Bohmong chieftain also sits on the Advisory Council for the [[Ministry of Chittagong Hill Tracts Affairs]] and the [[Bandarban Hill District Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peaceaccords.nd.edu/sites/default/files/accords/Chittagong_Hill_Tracts_Peace_Accord.pdf|title=Chittagong Hill Tracts Peace Accord|date=1997-12-02}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Bohmong chieftains claim descent from [[Tabinshwehti]] and [[Nanda Bayin]] of the [[First Toungoo Empire|Toungoo Empire]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lostfootsteps.org/en/history/the-history-of-raja-of-the-bohmong-circle|title=The history of Raja of the Bohmong Circle|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.horniman.ac.uk/get_involved/blog/five-go-collecting-kingly-swords|title=Five Go Collecting: Kingly Swords|last=Gardens|first=The Horniman Museum and|website=Horniman Museum and Gardens|language=en|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref> During British rule, the Chittagong Hill Tracts were administratively divided into three circles in 1884, namely the [[Chakma Circle]], the Bohmong Circle, and the [[Mong Circle]]<nowiki/>s, each presided over by a hereditary chief from the [[Chakma people|Chakma]] and [[Marma people]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GZtEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PR17&dq=bohmong+circle#v=onepage&q=bohmong%20circle&f=false|title=An Account of the Chittagong Hill Tracts|last=Hutchinson|first=Robert Henry Sneyd|date=1906|publisher=Bengal Secretariat Book Depot|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite report |last=Kundu|first=Debasish |last2=Samadder|first2=Mrinmoy |last3=Khan|first3=Ashrafuzzaman |last4=Shajahan Naomi|first4=Sharin |date=2011-01-04 |title=State of Justice in Chittagong Hill Tracts: Exploring the Formal and Informal Justice Institutions of Indigenous Communities |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281294250 |publisher=BRAC}}</ref> The circles were codified into law with the Chittagong Hill Tract Regulations, 1900, eased revenue collection and administrative burdens on British authorities by delegating tax collection, land administration management and social arbitration responsibilities to the chieftains.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-121974|title=Bandarban wears festive look as Rajpunyah starts|date=2010-01-15|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 1901, the Bohmong Circle extended {{Convert|2064|mi2|km2}}.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GZtEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA122&dq=hathi+linga#v=snippet&q=mong%20circle&f=false|title=An Account of the Chittagong Hill Tracts|last=Hutchinson|first=Robert Henry Sneyd|date=1906|publisher=Bengal Secretariat Book Depot|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> This administrative structure remained in place until 1964, when the introduction of local self-government abolished the special status of these circles and brought local administration under the control of the central government.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zaman|first=M. Q.|date=1982|title=Crisis in Chittagong Hill Tracts: Ethnicity and Integration|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=17|issue=3|pages=75\u201380|jstor=4370578}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bengal Zamindars}}\n\n[[Category:Bandarban District]]\n[[Category:Dynasties of India]]\n[[Category:Subdivisions of British India]]\n[[Category:History of Bengal]]\n[[Category:Quasi-princely estates of India]]\n[[Category:Lands inhabited by indigenous peoples]]\n[[Category:History of Chittagong Division]]\n", "name_user": "Falucidate", "label": "safe", "comment": "Missing comma added.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bohmong_Circle"}
